<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is getting late in the Thatcherfest and the BBC is nearing the bottom of
the barrel. Admittedly, it was not such a bad idea to wheel on Sir Bernard
Ingham for What The Papers Said (BBC2, 7.45). He analyses the five syndromes
which afflicted the press in its coverage of the Thatcher government,
including 'Columnar Pox' - wilful refusal to check facts.
However, it seems daft to make a programme about people's recollections of
what they were doing when Mrs Thatcher resigned? The Day She Went (BBC2,
9.30) hits the barrel base with a thump.
Thus far Plant Life (C4, 9.00) hovers around GCSE level in its explication
of plant physiology. Many viewers will be disappointed that it was not more
intellectually ambitious.
Demob (ITV, 9.00) is a comedy drama as limply wet as pondweed. It stars
Griff Rhys Jones as a demobbed soldier who joins up with a spivvish friend
to become variety show entertainers.
Cellist Jacqueline Du Pre is remembered in The Marquesa's Memoirs (Radio 3,
9.55), the enjoyable musical recollections of the Marquesa de Cadaval.
</TEXT>
