<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 93 / Benefits mistakes hit record Pounds 716m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MISTAKES IN the amount of social security paid to millions of unemployed
people, single parents and low-income pensioners have reached a record
level, the National Audit Office says today.
The public expenditure watchdog says that errors in the payment of income
support, the basic safety-net benefit, were Pounds 716m in 1992-93, 4.8 per
cent of the Pounds 15bn total.
Sir John Bourn, head of the watchdog, says that the Benefits Agency paid
claimants Pounds 575m more in income support than they were entitled to.
Much of this cannot be recovered because it is due to errors in calculating
and paying benefits, which are written off. Underpayments of Pounds 141m
will normally be paid when they are discovered.
Sir John, who is responsible for auditing the accounts of government
departments, has qualified the agency's accounts because of the errors.
More than Pounds 134m of the overpayments were due to problems in paying
claimants' mortgage interest direct to lenders, introduced last year as part
of measures to help reduce mortgage repossessions.
The value of errors has more than doubled in the past five years in spite of
efforts by the Benefits Agency to bring it down to 2 per cent of the value
of the benefit.
Mr Michael Bichard, the agency's chief executive, said that he had
introduced a series of measures to deal with the errors. These included
management reviews of the worst-performing offices, more automatic
processing of payments and additional checks on complex cases.
Sir John has also qualified the accounts over uncertainties about whether
correct payments have been made on housing benefit, where Pounds 82m has
been repaid to 89 local authorities for 1990-91 and 1991-92 on claims which
the auditors have been unable to verify.
There are also uncertainties about the amounts refunded to employers for
statutory sick pay and statutory maternity pay. The office has raised doubts
about the accuracy and completeness of employers' annual returns setting out
the amounts deducted from national insurance payments.
</TEXT>
