</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE National Audit Office has qualified the accounts of the Department of
Health over payments to health authorities. The main reason is the failure
of the National Health Service management executive to staunch losses at the
troubled South Birmingham health authority, John Willman writes.
The authority inherited losses of Pounds 10.5m when it was created in 1991
but there will be an accumulated deficit of Pounds 25m by April next year.
The authority's finances have continued to deteriorate, according to the
watchdog, in spite of a Pounds 16m package of support and close monitoring
by the West Midlands regional health authority.
In addition, the watchdog has qualified the accounts over an unauthorised
payment of Pounds 78,000 made by Wessex regional health authority to a
former director of information on leaving office.
The health authority is considering whether it can recover part or all of
the money.
