<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 93 / Discount clubs face strict tests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WAREHOUSE shopping clubs should still be assessed as retailers in spite of
Wednesday's ruling in the High Court that a local authority had been right
to treat the UK's first proposed discount club as a wholesaler, the
government said yesterday.
The UK's three biggest supermarket chains, J. Sainsbury, Tesco and Safeway,
had attempted to block the development, by US club operator Costco, at
Thurrock, Essex. They said that the warehouse should have been considered a
retailer, not a wholesaler, and been subjected to tougher planning criteria.
But Mr Justice Schiemann ruled on Wednesday that Thurrock was entitled to
assess the project as a wholesaler.
The Department of the Environment said yesterday it expected local
authorities to abide by its planning policy guidance note PPG6, issued in
July, which advised that 'planning decisions should regard (warehouse clubs)
as retail uses'.
The joint planning consultant for the three supermarket chains said
yesterday that Wednesday's judgment had not ended the debate over warehouse
clubs.
Mr John Littman of Rapleys, the commercial property agents, said: 'This
might be regarded as the first skirmish, but there are still many issues to
be decided.
Both Mr Littman and the DoE stressed yesterday that the judgment referred to
one case, where planning permission had been granted before the publication
of PPG6.
The department said its note did not seek to define warehouse clubs as
retailers or suggest that they should only be granted retail planning
consent. But it did advise that authorities should apply the same strict
tests to warehouse club applications as they did to retailers, regardless of
the type of planning permission sought.
Warehouse clubs sell a range of products from computers to cat food in huge,
spartan sheds at discount prices to fee-paying members.
Mr Littman said the three supermarket chains had not decided whether to
continue their battle to establish a legal definition of warehouse clubs as
retailers. They are debating whether to proceed with similar legal action
already initiated against UK cash and carry operator Nurdin &amp; Peacock, which
plans to open a warehouse club at Wednesbury, West Midlands.
Retailers' shares continued to fall amid market rumours that Sainsbury was
to launch a pre-Christmas price war.
Markets report, Page 38
</TEXT>
