<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 93 / Glass ceiling has no sign of cracks, survey claims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor and RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONLY 8 per cent of top executives in Britain are women, and the higher up
the corporate hierarchy, the fewer women there are, a survey of 29,000
executives in 533 companies shows.
Mr Paul Gregg and Mr Stephen Machin from the National Institute of Economic
and Social Research and the London School of Economics take issue with the
claim that women are increasing their share of the top executive jobs -
defined as ranging from chief executive level to senior middle management.
They also find that women are paid less than men even if working in the same
job.
'There does appear to be a glass ceiling blocking the promotion of women to
the highest jobs and it does not appear to be cracking,' they conclude.
The BBC Television network has reached its equality target for women in
senior positions, three years ahead of schedule, it announced yesterday,
Richard Donkin writes.
Ms Joanne Serpliss, deputy head of the BBC Television equal opportunities
department, told delegates at the Institute of Personnel Management
conference in Harrogate yesterday that the target had been reached earlier
in the year.
Is the Glass Ceiling Cracking? Gender Compensation Differentials and Access
to Promotion Among UK Executives. National Institute discussion paper No 50.
Tel 071 222 7665 ext 201.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Broadcasting Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
