<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 93 / Miners dig themselves into a corner: James Buxton explains
how an experiment in going-it-alone came to grief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'THERE'S a great deal of raw emotion among the lads today,' said Mr Jackie
Aitchison. 'They are extremely disappointed'.
Mr Aitchison was speaking about the reaction of the 167 miners who each
invested Pounds 10,000 in Monktonhall Mineworkers - the consortium of which
he is chairman - to the takeover offer by RJB Mining. This values their
stakes at Pounds 1,000 each, but they are being told there is no
alternative.
Raw emotion, sometimes bordering on paranoia, has been a recurring theme in
this sad story of the attempt by a consortium of miners to reopen a pit and
prove that they can make a profit where British Coal failed.
They are not alone in asking why financial support from government and local
authorities should be available now, when it was denied to the consortium
after it was formed in 1991.
The consortium's bid to take over Monktonhall was opposed by Labour members
of Lothian regional council. The National Union of Mineworkers was also
opposed to the project.
But the miners were supported by Conservative and other politicians, and in
December 1991 British Coal offered them the lease of the pit, rejecting a
bid by Caledonian Mining, a private mining company from Nottingham.
The miners met Mr David Heathcoat-Amory, then a junior energy minister, and
Mr Allan Stewart, Scottish Office industry minister. They received
encouragement but no financial assistance.
Price Waterhouse, the miners' financial advisers, failed to persuade any
financial institution to put money into Monktonhall, although Bank of
Scotland made a bridging loan which turned into a longer-term relationship,
now likely to end in a Pounds 1.8m write-off.
Instead the first 110 miners put in an astonishing Pounds 10,000 each,
mostly by borrowing, to raise Pounds 1.1m, thus guaranteeing themselves a
job. Mr Jim Parker, a former British Coal manager who was Monktonhall's
managing director, said that no one was deceived about the risks. He also
said: 'Men here in their 30s are going to make a lot of money at
Monktonhall'.
The company had the barest minimum of capital when it took over the mine in
June last year. But all would have been well, Mr Aitchison said yesterday,
if the miners had been able to start production that September and start
earning revenue.
Unfortunately much of the secondhand mining equipment which they had bought
failed, and they encountered adverse geological conditions in reopening the
first face. Mr Parker left the company in December. By the time full
production started in January the company was heavily in debt.
In late February Monktonhall announced that it was seeking an outside
investor, but when Caledonian Mining responded it was publicly brushed off.
In March, with the miners, now numbering 180, having worked for two weeks
without pay, Lothian region appointed the merchant bank Quayle Munro to
assess the situation. Quayle Munro reported that Monktonhall would be viable
only if new coal faces were opened up, costing Pounds 3m.
The bank then started looking for another investor.
RTZ and Hanson declined. On September 1 RJB Mining signed a letter of intent
and started guaranteeing the miners' wages.
The day before Quayle Munro had publicly criticised the consortium after it
sent a delegation to seek money from the Libyan government.
The miners face the loss of most of their investment but not of their jobs.
Recriminations over who is to blame are just starting.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Monktonhall Mineworkers.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
