<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 93 / Ford expects sharp fall in output
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORD OF Britain has warned that it expects a sharp fall in vehicle
production in the UK. The warning came yesterday as it offered a two-year
pay deal - a 1.8 per cent rise from next month and 2.5 per cent next year.
The company, which has lost more than Pounds 1m a day since 1990, is seeing
a small upturn in UK demand but that is more than cancelled out by a decline
from continental Europe.
Ford told unions that vehicle production in the UK was expected to fall to
392,000 this year from 447,000 last year, with the percentage for export
falling from 34 per cent last year to 19 per cent this year.
Ford management rejected the unions' claim for a 'substantial' pay rise and
a formal job security package, and hinted that the company's practice of
avoiding compulsory redundancy might have to be abandoned.
It also said that it wanted to reduce lay-off pay by 20 per cent. At present
workers laid off receive full basic pay, which cost the company Pounds 35m
in 1991 and last year.
Mr Jimmy Airlie, motor industry negotiator for the AEEU craft union, said:
'We're bitterly disappointed that they could not respond to our proposals on
job security. If it's good enough for Toyota, Nissan and Rover then it
should be good enough for Ford.'
The unions said they expect an improved offer when they meet again on
November 11. But the company will be reluctant to move further especially as
it now feels it paid too much in the two-year deal to next month. Union
officials took some consolation from the company's offer of greater employee
participation in the company pension fund.
Ford estimates that the overcapacity in the European car industry by the
late 1990s will reach 7m units. Ford itself is now using only about 70 per
cent of its European capacity and market share in the UK is continuing to
fall to about 21.7 per cent.
</TEXT>
