<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 93 / Takeover will leave workers out of pocket
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RJB MINING, the private Nottinghamshire mining company, yesterday made a
formal offer to take over Monktonhall Mineworkers, the miners' consortium
which operates a pit near Edinburgh, for Pounds 167,000.
The 167 members of the consortium, who each paid Pounds 10,000 for their
share, are being offered Pounds 1,000 per share.
The board of Monktonhall is recommending the miners to accept the offer. It
is telling them that if they do not do so the company will go into
liquidation. It lost Pounds 3.7m in the year ended May 31 and has net
liabilities of Pounds 2m.
The offer from RJB Mining, which was floated on the stock exchange in June,
is likely to end the shortlived coal miners' consortium which leased
Monktonhall from British Coal last year. It was undercapitalised and
suffered initial production difficulties in spite of having contracts to
sell its output.
The takeover would avert liquidation but would mean Bank of Scotland, the
secured creditor, writing off Pounds 1.8m. RJB would invest Pounds 3m in
developing Monktonhall and expect to receive a subsidy from the Department
of Trade and Industry.
Lothian regional council, which refused to help Monktonhall Mineworkers when
it was formed, would provide a subsidy. Scottish Power would remain
Monktonhall's main customer.
The directors of Monktonhall Mineworkers will resign if the offer is
accepted and Mr Bert Brown, the managing director, will leave.
RJB would offer shareholders who took voluntary severance the sum of Pounds
3,000. Those who remained employees would have a production-related bonus
scheme which, if targets were met, would mean payments of up to Pounds 3,000
for next year and a further Pounds 1,000 for 1995. RJB expects to retain
almost all the current workforce 182 men.
The miners have until November 18 to decide on the offer. RJB is insisting
on a 90 per cent level of acceptance to make the offer valid.
Mr Jackie Aitchison, chairman of Monktonhall, said it was disappointing that
Monktonhall had not been able to go it alone.
He refused to say whether anyone had let the consortium down, or comment on
the fact that the DTI and Lothian region, which were now offering finance,
had previously refused it.
For RJB the purchase of Monktonhall, which has current capacity of 300,000
tonnes a year, is a chance to expand its deep-mined output.
</TEXT>
