<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 93 / Ministers deadlocked on public spending cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT remained deadlocked on public spending cuts yesterday after
ministers failed to reach agreement at a marathon three-hour cabinet
meeting.
Downing Street said 'substantial progress' had been made on a package of
spending cuts presented to the cabinet by the EDX expenditure committee. But
Mr John Major, the prime minister, was forced to refer the issue to a
special cabinet meeting on Tuesday after several spending ministers objected
to the EDX proposals.
Ministers said much of yesterday's cabinet was taken up with discussions on
Ulster, rail privatisation, the Sheehy report on reforms to the police
service and today's European Community summit.
The most trenchant opposition to the EDX package came from Mr Malcolm
Rifkind, defence secretary, who has fought against proposed cuts of up to
Pounds 1bn. Mr Rifkind is understood to have headed off a significant
proportion of the threatened cuts, partly by threatening to call for a
full-scale defence review. He warned, however, that any attempt to make more
than token cuts in the Pounds 23bn defence budget risked provoking a
substantial backbench rebellion.
Fourteen Conservative MPs have written to Mr Major threatening to oppose
substantial defence cuts. Several other Tories are thought to sympathise
with the rebels.
Other ministers objected to the EDX package, including Mr John MacGregor,
transport secretary, Mr John Gummer, environment secretary, Mr Peter Lilley,
social security secretary, and Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary.
Most other ministers are understood to be happy with the EDX
recommendations, which are intended to implement the cabinet's earlier
decision to limit next year's public spending total to Pounds 253.6bn.
There was a degree of optimism that the critical ministers would fall into
line on Tuesday, removing the need to reopen negotiations.
Mr Major has made clear to the spending ministers, however, that he will not
hesitate to refer the whole package to EDX if necessary. This has increased
pressure on ministers to settle on Tuesday or risk seeing their budgets
further reduced in a fresh round of argument in EDX.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, is keen to reach early agreement on
spending so that he can finalise the revenue side of the first unified
Budget, to be delivered on November 30. But he faces deep divisions among
Tory backbenchers over the balance to be struck between spending cuts and
tax increases.
Joe Rogaly, Page 16
</TEXT>
