<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 93 / DTI urged to delay British Gas split
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GAS Consumers Council has asked the government to delay decisions on the
future of British Gas until an inquiry has examined the impact on consumers
of proposals to break up the company and possibly abolish its monopoly.
Mr James Cooper, chairman of the council, yesterday said the proposed
inquiry should focus on whether the abolition of British Gas' monopoly of
supply to small-scale, mostly residential customers, would result in a
'measureable benefit to the majority'. He added that if the inquiry also
said there would be no substantial price rise for a minority of low-income
customers and no threat to supplies, then 'the monopoly should be abolished
without delay'.
In a submission to the Department of Trade and Industry the council said it
could not support many of the recent recommendations of the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission for introducing greater competition into the gas market.
The council was particularly concerned that the MMC wanted the cost of
breaking up British Gas to be paid for by consumers.
Mr Cooper also criticised the recommendation that British Gas' monopoly
threshold should fall from 2,500 therms a year to 1,500 therms in 1997.
Below the threshold British Gas is the monopoly supplier. The change would
benefit only 400,000 households, he said.
</TEXT>
