<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 93 / US growth of 2.8% pushes Dow to high
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US economy expanded at a real annual rate of 2.8 per cent in the third
quarter, the best performance this year, thanks to steady growth in consumer
spending and industrial production, the Commerce Department said yesterday.
Inflation fell to its lowest level in seven years.
Evidence of a non-inflationary and stronger recovery, together with some
better than expected corporate profits, pushed the Dow Jones industrial
average up 23.20 points to close at a new high of 3,687.86, beating Monday's
record of 3,673.61. The index traded briefly above 3,700 before investors
stepped in to take profits.
The gross domestic product improvement would have been even better but for
the impact of this summer's Midwest flooding, which cut 0.6 per cent off the
quarterly return. In the first two quarters, GDP rose by 0.8 per cent and
1.9 per cent respectively.
Growth was widespread across the economy, according to the department's
initial estimates for the quarter, apart from the farm and defence sectors.
Consumer spending rose by 4.2 per cent in the quarter, up from 3.4 per cent
in the previous three months, a clear response to continued low interest
rates.
This was also reflected in a lower personal savings rate, down to 3.7 per
cent from 4.4 per cent.
Mr Ron Brown, the commerce secretary, noted that interest-sensitive sectors
appeared to be leading the recovery. He pointed to the expansion of consumer
durable equipment (up 9 per cent), residential construction (up 10.1 per
cent) and durable goods (up 7.5 per cent).
Inflation pressures also abated in the third quarter, down to an annual rate
of 1.8 per cent from the 2.9 per cent of the previous three months,
according to the Commerce Department's fixed-weight price index for gross
domestic purchases. This is the lowest quarterly increase in the index since
1986.
President Bill Clinton, pre-empting a report due out later in the day, also
announced that the budget deficit in the fiscal year ending last month had
fallen to Dollars 255bn (Pounds 169bn), 12 per cent lower than the Dollars
290.2bn of fiscal 1992. He claimed this was evidence his economic policies
were working.
A fistful of private economic forecasts foresaw even higher growth in GDP in
the final three months. The Conference Board predicted a real 3.4 per cent,
while Merrill Lynch was more bullish with its 4-5 per cent estimate.
There remains some concern that the current growth cycle may resemble that
of last year, when an anaemic first half was transformed into a 5.7 per cent
expansion in the final quarter.
This came too late to help President George Bush's re-election campaign and
was succeeded by minimal growth in the first half of this year.
The main negative non-farm elements in the third quarter were found in a
widening trade deficit, with exports down 1.1 per cent and imports up 1.9
per cent, although this was a more modest increase than previously, and in
reduced government purchases, down 6.1 per cent on lower defence orders.
</TEXT>
<XX>
