<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 93 / Berlin airports seek private cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS to expand Berlin's airport capacity are expected to be financed by the
private sector in a move signalling a gradual shift from public sector
borrowing for infrastructure projects.
Investment bank Barclays de Zoete Wedd has been appointed to advise Berlin
Brandenburg Flughafen Holding (BBF) how the existing structure, and the
construction of a new airport, can be financed privately.
BBF, a holding company whose shareholders include the German government,
which has a 26 per cent stake, the state of Brandenburg (37 per cent) and
the city of Berlin (37 per cent), runs the city's three airports: Tegel,
Templehof, and Schonefeld. All three are operating at close to capacity;
nearly 10m passengers used them last year. Also, Templehof may be closed by
1996 because it is virtually in the city centre.
Mr Michael McGhee, a director of BZW in London, said: This is the first time
an airport authority in Germany had considered approaching the private
sector for financing a major infrastructure project.' In the past, the money
to build airports has been raised by debt through the banks.
An official from the Senate, Berlin's government, said yesterday the city
was aiming to become the hub for for central and eastern Europe.
The shift to the private sector coincides with attempts by the states of
Brandeburg and Berlin to contain their budget deficits. Berlin this year
overshot its budget by DM5.8bn.
</TEXT>
