<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / BCCI creditors face long delay after court ruling: Appeal
against liquidators' plans upheld in Luxembourg
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THOUSANDS of creditors of Bank of Credit and Commerce International may face
a delay of several more years before receiving any compensation for the
millions they lost when the bank collapsed.
This follows a surprise decision by the Luxembourg courts yesterday
upholding an appeal against plans by the liquidators for an agreement with
Abu Dhabi which could have led to a payout next year.
The decision represented a victory for three individual creditors who have
persistently argued in the English and Luxembourg courts against the
liquidators' agreement with the government of Abu Dhabi, the majority
shareholder in the bank. It jeopardises the agreement by which Abu Dhabi
would have contributed more than Dollars 1.7bn to the liquidators for
distribution to creditors, in exchange for a waiver of all legal claims
against it.
Mr Brian Smouha, one of threeliquidators to BCCI appointed by the Luxembourg
courts and the man who negotiated the agreement with Abu Dhabi, warned that
the decision might trigger legal actions and delay payments for as much as
10 years.
'We were disappointed,' said Mr Smouha, a partner with accountants Touche
Ross. 'This has caused there to be no money in the hands of the creditors.
Now they can face only uncertainties.'
Mr Keith Vaz, the opposition Labour MP who has championed the cause of BCCI
creditors, called for the UK government to intervene in bringing about a
settlement. But Downing Street said last night that the government was not a
party to the Luxembourg hearing, and would not be involved in further legal
action. It said compensation was a matter for Touche Ross, the liquidator,
'if they want to take it further'.
Judge Raul Gretsch told the Luxembourg court of appeal yesterday morning:
'The appeal is justified and the liquidators have no right to sign an
agreement.'
The ruling has destroyed the prospect of a ballot by the liquidators of
BCCI's estimated 530,000 worldwide creditors on their plans, which could
have led to a payment of 15p in the pound to creditors next August.
The Luxembourg liquidators are due to meet today to discuss their options in
advance of a meeting of BCCI liquidators around the world on Wednesday and
Thursday next week.
They will consider appealing the judgment, attempting to renegotiate with
Abu Dhabi, or suing it to gain more money. But Mr Julien Roden, one of the
Luxembourg liquidators, yesterday appeared to rule out an appeal. 'The court
has decided. We are court-appointed liquidators and we will follow what the
court has decided - that's my first reaction,' he said.
Mr Adil Elias, one of the three creditors who brought the appeal, said: 'We
had confidence that the Luxembourg courts would listen.'
He said his action was brought on behalf of 1,000 creditors from 24
countries in the Depositors' Protection Association who are owed Dollars
500m. He said they had supported him 'financially and emotionally' during
the case, which had cost 'a few million'.
Liquidators try to put brave face on ruling, Page 6
</TEXT>
