<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Survey of International Capital Markets (9): Pace may slow
down - United States
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR THE third consecutive year, Wall Street is asking itself: how long can
the good times last? Two years ago, investment banks and securities houses
were enjoying buoyant markets and surging profits, but doubting whether the
momentum could be sustained for another 12 months.
In 1992, business got even better, and again Wall Street was unsure whether
it could last. But it did. Now, two thirds of the way through a
record-breaking 1993, much the same question is back on people's lips. Is
1994 going to be the year when profits come down from the stratosphere?
While no one is predicting that the financial markets or Wall Street's
earnings will fall into a serious slump next year, a slowdown from a
record-breaking pace of growth is expected, if only for the reason that it
is hard to imagine that the pace of earnings growth in the securities
industry can be maintained for another year.
Whatever happens, matching the performance of 1991-1993 will be difficult.
Since 1990, when New York Stock Exchange member firms posted a loss of
Dollars 106m, the industry's after-tax profits have improved in leaps and
bounds. In 1991, profits jumped to Dollars 3.8bn. In 1992, they climbed to
Dollars 4.1bn.
So far this year, many of the biggest US investment banks and securities
houses have announced record quarterly earnings. In the first half of the
year, NYSE member firms profits reached Dollars 3.08bn. Barring a market
crash or a big surge in domestic interest rates in the final months of this
year, industry profits for 1993 should break last year's record comfortably.
Although a variety of factors have fuelled Wall Street's earnings
juggernaut, including heavy demand for securities from individual investors
and strong growth in the asset management business, the key to firms'
successes in the domestic capital markets has been the very low level of US
interest rates.
Nowhere have low interest rates had more of an effect than in proprietary
trading and investment banking. Traditionally, Wall Street firms make a lot
of their profits by borrowing heavily against their securities holdings and
investing or trading that money in the markets. Over the past three years,
low interest rates have made this leveraged business even more profitable
than usual.
By borrowing cheaply on the short-term markets, and using that capital to
speculate on rapid swings in securities, interest rates or currencies, or to
invest in higher-yielding long-term assets, securities houses and
investments have earned billions of dollars in profits. On Wall Street over
the past few years, trading revenues (especially in the fixed-income
markets) have been growing at a faster rate than any other form of revenues.
In 1992, they totalled Dollars 16.3bn, up from Dollars 9.9bn four years
earlier.
The success of proprietary trading has led to one particularly interesting
development - the rise of the trader as manager. Over the past year
executives who made their reputation on the trading floors of Wall Street
have been appointed to key management positions at a number of leading
firms, including Morgan Stanley, Merrill Lynch, and Lehman Brothers. In many
cases, the traders have earned promotion at the expense of the investment
bankers and dealmakers, who for more than a decade have ruled the roost on
Wall Street.
This trend has led some observers to claim that the industry is undergoing a
fundamental shift in the balance of its business, away from corporate
finance and advisory work and towards a greater emphasis on proprietary
trading. Yet the changes appear more cyclical than structural in nature.
Trading revenues are strong primarily because interest rates are so low.
Once rates pick up again, trading revenues will probably suffer, and traders
will eventually lose their spot at the top of Wall Street's food chain.
Although traders may be grabbing more of the limelight these days, their
counterparts in investment banking have been no slouches either. Revenues
from stock and bond underwriting have been extremely buoyant over the past
18months. Again, low interest rates are the key. Eager to raise money to
refinance old, expensive debt, to pay for much-needed restructurings, or to
fund expansion, companies have been rushing to the public markets to take
advantage of the lowest borrowing rates in 30 years.
Last year, companies raised a record Dollars 851.7bn through debt and equity
offerings, shattering the previous record, set in 1991, of Dollars 589.6bn.
So far this year, volume has been even heavier, with Dollars 532bn raised in
the first six months. At the end of June, many observers felt that the
market may have peaked because it looked as if interest rates had bottomed.
Since then, however, fresh declines in long-term rates have kept the
momentum going, and could push public securities offerings through the
Dollars 1,000bn barrier this year.
And it is not just US companies that have been issuing record amounts of
debt and equity. Foreign companies have been coming to the US capital
markets in increasing numbers, not just because raising funds in the US has
been so inexpensive, but because US investors, traditionally so reluctant to
invest outside their country, have been buying more foreign stock and bond
issues in their search for big returns.
Low interest rates have also helped boost the equity underwriting business,
because investors, looking for something better than the 3 per cent they get
on short-term assets, have been snapping up new share issues in record
amounts. This, combined with the steady rise in stock prices, has sustained
a long and profitable boom in equity issuance.
As for what happens to the capital markets next year, much hinges on the
movement of interest rates. Analysts have been surprised that interest rates
have fallen so far (the yield on the long bond fell below 6 per cent this
summer for the first time in 16 years, and short-term yields have been
trading at 30-year lows), so they have become wary about predicting where
rates are headed next.
</TEXT>
