<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Survey of International Capital Markets (10): Welcome boost
for companies - Japan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE companies, facing the need for financing more than ever before
because of the depressed cash flow from falling profits and rising costs,
have welcomed the rise in the Tokyo stock market since August.
Thanks to the ministry of finance propping up the stock market by pumping in
public pension funds, the Nikkei average has recovered 41 per cent from its
six-year low, and companies have piled in to raise funds through
equity-linked issues.
A survey taken by the Nikkei Newsletter on Bond and Money, indicated that
during the first six months of the business year to September, manufacturers
saw a 4.9 per cent fall in cash flow from the previous year, while
non-manufacturers faced a 9.7 per cent decline. A rise in redemption of
equity-linked bonds issued during the economic 'bubble' of the late 1980s is
also still squeezing cashflow at companies.
Domestic issuance of convertible bonds rose 2.2 times to Y722bn during the
first six months to June. On the overseas markets, Japanese companies issued
USDollars 7.3bn in warrant bonds, 47 per cent higher than the previous year,
and USDollars 2.2bn in convertible bonds, an 11 per cent decline.
On the overseas markets, companies shifted from the Eurodollar market to the
Swiss market, due to lower costs and an easing in underwriting regulations.
Eurodollar equity-linked issues fell 55.9 per cent during the April-June
quarter to Y153.7bn from the previous quarter, but Swiss franc issues rose
2.1 times to Y244.1bn.
The securities industry is hoping the ministry of finance will lift its ban
on share offerings by listed companies, which has been in place since the
market plunged in 1990, after Tuesday's debut by East Japan Railway.
Meanwhile, corporate financiers point out that more Japanese companies,
facing deteriorating earnings and a stock market which has moved sideways
around the 20,000 level since mid-April, have been forced to turn to the
straight bond market rather than to equity-linked financing.
'You need a volatile market for investors to become interested in
equity-linked investments,' points out Mr Alan Livsey at Kleinwort Benson in
Tokyo.
According to the Bond Underwriters Association of Japan, Japanese companies
raised a record Y59.5bn during September. Traders say that historically low
interest rates also prompted the sharp increase, but companies face higher
costs by raising capital through domestic corporate bonds rather than
through equity-linked paper overseas.
A growing awareness within the ministry of finance of the need for optional
fund-raising measures amid the sluggish stock market and increasing
reluctance among banks to lend, have prompted the gradual liberalisation of
the domestic bond market. Last April, the ministry eased restrictions on
companies eligible to finance on the corporate bond market.
The emergency economic package announced last month also included the
introduction of new products, such as bonds with shorter maturities and
floating rate notes.
However, the lack of a liquid secondary market, due to the 'buy and hold'
strategy of most Japanese institutional investors, where once a bond is
bought it is kept until maturity, has been a barrier to fully-fledged growth
of the bond market.
Foreign issuers are also concerned that the credit ratings are not properly
reflected on bond prices. The lack of price differentiation between issuers
with high credit ratings and low credit ratings is prompting an increasing
number of overseas issuers with triple-A credit ratings to move away from
the samurai market.
Mr Mikio Fujii at Nomura Securities' fixed income department, laments:
'Japan's Samurai market is turning into a junk bond market because issuers
with low credit ratings can issue at relatively cheap cost.'
Market participants point out that several factors are preventing the
domestic bond market from becoming more sophisticated. One reason is that
many Japanese fund managers still do not evaluate options according to
investment returns, making them oblivious of credit risk and pricing of the
bonds. Financing costs are higher due to the trustee fees paid to banks,
which act as guarantors in the case of a bankruptcy. The lack of a central
clearing system for corporate bonds and the complicated registration
procedure for transferring bonds from one investor to another, are also
hampering growth of the secondary market.
The ministry of finance and brokers have finally started to work on solving
some of the structural problems. The ministry has called on a group of
academics and members of the financial industry to study reforms for the
secondary market.
Meanwhile, Moody's Investors Service, the US credit ratings agency, says
that attitudes of Japanese institutional investors towards credit risk, are
gradually changing.
Mr Masaru Kakutani, representative director of Moody's Japan, says investors
are becoming more aware of credit risks at companies. This is because banks
have become more reluctant to take on risks as trustees, and deregulation
has allowed less creditworthy companies to raise funds.
</TEXT>
<XX>
