<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Survey of International Capital Markets (7): Flexible friend
for lenders - Securitisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
US BANKS and companies have been reaping the benefits of securitisation for
years, but their European counterparts are much more recent converts to this
flexible form of balance sheet management.
Securitisation is a funding process which allows banks or companies to take
loans off their balance sheets, thereby removing the risk of default and
freeing capital which can be used to make new loans.
'The main objective of securitisation is to achieve capital efficiency and
to maximise returns on shareholders' funds,' says Mr Guy Fletcher, director
of BZW Asset Securitisation Group, part of Barclays Bank.
In October, Barclays became the first UK bank to securitise personal loans
when it raised Pounds 280m through an issue of floating rate notes backed by
loans made to the bank's credit card customers.
Securitisation works in this way: the originator of the loans (that is, the
bank or company) places the loans in a special-purpose vehicle which then
raises money by selling debt securities, backed by these assets, to
investors. Interest payments on the so-called mortgage-backed or
asset-backed securities are funded as the borrowers make repayments on their
loans.
Most of the loans which are securitised tend to be residential mortgages or
consumer loans from banks, credit card companies, car manufacturers or
leasing companies.
Securitisation of commercial property loans is also increasing in the US,
reflecting an unwillingness among banks to expose themselves too heavily to
the commercial property developers after the property crash of the late
1980s.
Although the banks or companies do not rid themselves entirely of the risk
of default, their exposure is reduced considerably. Securitisation experts
say they sometimes end up being responsible for the first losses on as
little as 1 per cent of the total volume of securitised loans.
Securitisation is firmly established in the US, where about half of the
Dollars 2,500bn worth of residential mortgages are estimated to have been
securitised. In addition, asset-backed securities make up about Dollars 75bn
of the Dollars 600bn corporate commercial paper market in the US.
Current volume of securities backed by commercial property loans in the US
is around Dollars 12bn but this market is expected to grow rapidly in the
next three years when Dollars 300bn worth of commercial property loans will
need to be re-financed.
By comparison, securitisation in Europe is still at an early stage. Most of
Europe's securitised deals have originated in the UK though there has been
activity in Spain, France and Scandinavia.
In the UK, the most active issuers in the mortgage-backed market have been
centralised mortgage lenders looking for funding to match the long maturity
of their portfolios.
Securitised deals were launched in the Eurobond market in 1985. Volume rose
rapidly from Dollars 200m that year to Dollars 12.8bn in 1990 but then
nearly halved to Dollars 7.2bn in 1992 as the economic recession and high
interest rates in the UK cut demand for new loans. However, there has been a
revival this year (Dollars 5.5bn has been raised) as lenders seek to expand
their business without having to raise fresh capital.
Mr Malcolm Veale, head of asset securitisation of National Westminster Bank,
the UK's high street bank which raised Pounds 300m from its first
mortgage-backed issue in September, gives several reasons why securitisation
has been slow to get off the ground in Europe.
First, European companies have not the same access to information technology
(IT) as their US counterparts to enable them to build up data on the
performance of their loans or leases.
International credit-rating agencies are only willing to give a rating to a
mortgage-backed or asset-backed issue if they have several years' worth of
data on the assets backing the securities.
Mr Veale says that European companies are becoming more conscious of the
importance of ratings and have started to compile the necessary information
on their loans. However, they are still several years away from being able
to securitise these assets.
He also notes that the actual volumes of credit card receivables which could
be securitised in Europe are not as vast as in the US. For example, credit
cards have taken off in Germany only in the past few years.
The lack of a domestic market means that any European company or bank
wanting to securitise assets would have to tap the market in the US or the
UK. But the cost of hedging their currency positions could make the
transaction uneconomic.
Another drawback to the growth of securitisation in Europe is the lack of
regulation on off-balance-sheet financing. In many countries in Europe,
virtually no guidelines have been laid down.
In the UK, the Accounting Standards Board's financial reporting exposure
draft on off-balance-sheet financing is expected to become an accounting
standard by the end of the year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
