<DATE>931028
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Survey of International Capital Markets (8): Nightmare for
harmonisers - Regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRIAN BOLLEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE international capital markets are a regulator's nightmare:
responsibility is split not only between different geographical
jurisdictions, but also between banks and securities houses.
However, the spread of EC-wide regulation is forcing greater standardisation
of Europe's financial markets.
'Regulators are not targeting the Euromarkets but are targeting certain
activities,' says Mr Jean-Pierre Wellens, chairman of the International
Primary Market Association. 'EC regulators are trying to set a standard for
financial transactions in the EC, and international regulators like the Bank
for International Settlements also impact on the market.'
Recently, the European Community's directives on Capital Adequacy (CAD) and
Investment Services (ISD) - the cornerstones of EC law on the investment
markets - have been the centre of attention. The revised regulatory
framework is seen as opening the prospect of a single capital market
throughout the EC, providing financial institutions with a single EC
passport to exploit opportunities.
The ISD is designed to harmonise regulation of financial services across
Europe, and the CAD is designed to provide a common basis for determining
the capital banks have to put aside to support certain activities; the goal
is a level playing field. Both directives have been adopted and member
states need to translate them into local law, by January 1, 1996.
Unfortunately, the revised framework is also seen as possibly putting
EC-based banks and securities houses at a disadvantage with non-EC
competitors who do not have to adhere to international standards; the
pressure for the level playing field is less in the US and Japan than in
Europe.
The debate might be over but that does not mean an end to uncertainty and
anxiety. The focus has shifted from the contents of the two directives to
the possibility of misinterpretation, deliberate or otherwise, by member
states clinging to cherished protectionist ways. The main concerns of the
International Primary Market Association (IPMA) are that artificial and
inappropriate obstacles could be erected that would reduce the
cost-effectiveness and flexibility of the 'immensely successful' markets. It
is vital, it says, that institutions are not artificially put at a cost
disadvantage to competitors in other markets. On the other hand, the
increasing scale of government borrowing means it is obviously in the
interests of European governments to be able to raise funds locally on
competitive terms.
Success in winning mandates from outside the European time zone also makes
the markets an important source of foreign earnings for Europe. 'European
regulators understand that this is a market which lives by competition, and
that it is of vital strategic importance to the European economy,' says Mr
Dirk Hazell, secretary-general of IPMA.
Other concerns are that regulators will be unable to resist the temptation
to impose regulations over and above the CAD/ISD requirements. 'Regulators'
objectives, one of which must be to permit the markets to work efficiently,
are more likely to be achieved if regulators work with the grain of the
market and having consulted leading practitioners, than if rules are
suddenly imposed from an ivory tower; in this case their practical
application may well prove uncertain,' says Mr Hazell.
Deliberate misinterpretation is thought unlikely, if politicians have
learned anything, that is, from the ERM experience. 'Market forces cannot be
resisted indefinitely,' says Mr John Langton, chief executive of the
International Secondary Market Association (ISMA). 'Markets smell
unsustainable financial policies pretty quickly.'
Mr Christopher Cruickshank, principal administrator at the European
Commission's DGXV, the directorate-general responsible for internal market
and financial services, puts less emphasis on the possibility of
misinterpretation. 'We would like to organise continuing discussions aimed
at ensuring harmonised implementation,' he says. National supervisors, for
their part, will be watching each other like hawks.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
    P6211 Security Brokers and Dealers.
    P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
