<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Survey of International Capital Markets (3): Winning streak
continues - Government bonds have enjoyed a phenomenal run
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER a phenomenal 18-month run, the rally in global government bonds has
already exeeded most observers' expectations.
But the end of the bull run is proving very difficult to call. Institutional
investors are scared that if they take profits now they could miss a further
leg of the rally - as happened to some US Treasury investors during the
summer - and have to buy back in at a more expensive level.
Company treasurers are also getting twitchy. They want to raise long-term
debt at the lowest possible interest rates, but every time they feel ready
to lock in fixed-rate funding, long-term bond yields fall further.
And, as with Las Vegas gamblers on an unprecedented winning streak, each
favourable turn of the roulette wheel increases the tension for the next
time. Now the questions are: where and when is the rally finally going to
end?
The first question breaks up into four possible areas: the UK, the European
high-yielding countries, the mainstream EC markets and the US. And it
prompts the subsidiary question of why the winning streak is going to end,
ie which investment power, Japan the US or Europe, is going to pull the
plug?
These questions have prompted fevered debate in the UK where nominal
long-term interest rates, reflected by 15-year government bonds, have fallen
from 8.4 per cent in June to just over 7 per cent last week, the lowest
level since the sixties. For the past few months many UK fund managers
steeped in the tradition of boom-bust economics have believed that it cannot
continue and while they have not gone so far as to take their money out of
the gilts market they have not been putting any more in. The rise in prices
and subsequent fall in yields has been led by overseas investors. They have
looked at the fundamental economic position rather than the historical
perspective and are more prepared than their UK counterparts to believe in a
sustained period of slow growth and flat inflation.
In fact, some economists believe the UK's traditional enthusiasm for
inflating itself out of trouble may have changed at a fundamental level. Mr
Simon Briscoe, economist with SG Warburg Securities, argues that 'a low
inflation psychology is developing in the UK'. Also, the trend towards
mortgages at rates fixed for several years will make it harder to tinker
with the economy via short-term interest rates and more dependent on low
interest long-term borrowing.
Amazement surrounding the UK market is almost matched by the surprise at the
performance of the southern European countries generally referred to as the
high yielders - Spain, Italy and Portugal. These three countries,
traditionally dogged by rocketing inflation, have seen 10-year rates plunge
since last autumn. Spain's benchmark yield, the standard by which other
forms of public and corporate borrowing are set, has tumbled from above 14
per cent last October to below 8.5 per cent recently. The return on
equivalent Italian bond yields which take into consideration a 12.5 per cent
tax charge for overseas residents has slipped to around 8.8 per cent from
14.7 per cent in October. In Portugal, short-term rates fell by 6.75 points
to 10.25 per cent between May and July.
These high-yielding markets have been heavily supported because they have so
much further to fall than their more stolid European neighbours. France and
Germany, which form the hard core of the exchange rate mechanism, have also
fallen significantly. At the moment they are in limbo as Germany struggles
to maintain high rates to combat the inflationary by-product of its
unification programme and France refuses to cut rates because it is
determined to attach itself to its neighbour's monetary coat tails.
But just when European investors began to wonder if there were more exciting
opportunities elsewhere, Japanese buyers moved in, determined to make the
most of a very expensive yen. Also, Goldman Sachs, the US investment bank
which recently advised its clients to shift equity holdings from the UK to
mainland Europe, says continental bond markets remain popular. 'We are
positive on all the major European markets and US investors are still
pouring in money,' says one Goldmans trader.
The US interest is a reflection of the astounding performance of the US
Treasury market. At the beginning of September the yield on the benchmark
30-year bond had fallen below 6 per cent, the lowest return in its 16-year
life. At the same time, several brokerage houses were warning that the
market was close to overheating, arguing that investors had underestimated
the strength of the economy.
It may be one of the classic cliches that when things happen they happen
first in the US, but that could be the case with the end of the global rally
in government bonds. When the economy picks up inflation will turn round and
send yields bouncing upwards.
As to timing it largely depends whether investors start to panic and the
signs are that most US institutional fund mangers are sanguine to the point
of being phlegmatic. Economists are also divided in spite of the historic
lows achieved by 30-year US bonds.
Yamaichi, the Japanese bank, believes the US outlook is improving and
long-term debt prices are out of touch with the inflationary pressure that
any pick-up will impose. On the other hand Goldman Sachs say growth remains
low, inflation is being skewed by high prices in some commodities and bond
yields should 'continue to drift lower as time passes'. Its US rival,
Salomon Brothers, also believes that the prospect of a US rate rise has
receded and advises its clients to remain overweight in US Treasuries.
Perhaps the best that can be said is that when the spectre of inflation
returns it is more likely to be roaming the streets of Manhattan than the
boulevards of Paris.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
