<DATE>931028
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Survey of International Capital Markets (2): Record surge in
new issues - International Bond Markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE downward spiral in interest rates this year has helped to boost the
volume of new issues in the international bond markets above the record
level reached in 1992, and the upward trend is showing no signs of running
out of steam.
New volume stood at Dollars 301.25bn at the end of September, easily
surpassing 1992's record total of Dollars 267.7bn, according to data from
IFR Securities Data.
The fall in interest rates has had a dual effect on the international bond
markets, encouraging both borrowers and investors to participate actively.
On the one hand, the lower interest rates have encouraged borrowers to lock
in long-term financing at what many of them regard to be the bottom of the
interest rate cycle. On the other, the erosion of returns on cash deposits
has prompted investors to seek higher yields by investing in the bond
market.
Politics has also played its part in the surge of new issues. Several bouts
of turmoil in the financial markets in 1992 and this year, due to
uncertainty over the future of the European exchange rate mechanism, have
forced some central banks in Europe and the Nordic region to intervene
heavily to restore stability to their respective currencies.
As a result, they have had to replenish their depleted foreign exchange
reserves by borrowing in the international bond markets where they can raise
large amounts very quickly.
The Nordic countries have also had to increase their funding requirements to
finance their yawning budget deficits. Their heavy borrowing programmes
placed corporate borrowers from those countries at a severe disadvantage
earlier in the year because they were forced to pay significant premiums
over the spreads paid by sovereign issuers.
However, now that a large part of the sovereign borrowing programmes has
been completed, the spreads - that is, the premium over the yield on
government bonds - paid by Nordic corporate borrowers have come down
sharply.
Corporate yield spreads have also tightened because demand for long-dated,
non-government paper has far outstripped supply, particularly in the
Eurosterling sector. According to SG Warburg Securities corporate unsecured
index, the spread over UK government bonds for maturities of 10 years or
more has fallen from 153 basis points at the end of 1992 to around 95 basis
points.
Long-dated paper is in demand because investors are having to look further
along the yield curve to secure high yields, since they are no longer
available at the short end. In the dollar sector, where yields have fallen
to a 25-year low, supply of long-dated paper has fallen dramatically due to
tha decision by the US Treasury to auction fewer 30-year bonds.
In view of this demand, Italy gave a greater weighting to the 30-year than
to the 10-year tranche of its first global bond offering, which was launched
in September.
Italy's global offering, which raised Dollars 5.5bn, set a record for this
type of international bond deal, which permits issuers to tap the large US
domestic bond market. The previous record of Dollars 3bn was held by the
province of Ontario.
The World Bank, which pioneered the global bond concept, has also been an
active issuer of global bonds this year. In September, it issued its ninth
dollar global bond offering which was priced to yield 10 basis points over
the yield on underlying US Treasuries, the tightest spread the World Bank
has achieved on its 10-year dollar global bonds.
This partly reflected the general tightening of spreads in the market as
well as the fact that the offering was significantly over-subscribed.
However, the tight spread and the balanced distribution worldwide also show
that the World Bank has achieved the main aims of its global bond programme
which was launched four years ago. They were to achieve a truly global
distribution and a single world price for its bonds.
The World Bank has also issued global bonds in yen and expects to launch its
first D-Mark global bond in the fourth quarter of this year.
This year has also seen a large increase in the issuance of floating rate
notes (FRNs) as issuers tap demand from investors for high-yielding
instruments at a time of falling interest rates.
According to IFR Securities Data, Dollars 45bn worth of floating rate notes
were issued from January to mid-September, compared with Dollars 38bn for
the whole of 1992.
Most floating rate notes offer investors a way to achieve a higher income
than they would receive from a fixed-rate bond because the notes tend to pay
a premium over the London interbank offered rate (Libor).
This year has also seen variations on the floating rate note. One
instrument, the 'collared' FRN, has a minimum interest rate and a maximum
interest rate. Under this structure, the holder receives a higher return
than current money market rates but will not benefit if rates rise above the
maximum interest rate set by the issuer.
The 'reverse' FRN pays a higher return as interest rates fall. This is
achieved by fixing the coupon at a certain interest rate minus Libor,
therefore when Libor falls the coupon gets bigger.
The activity in the international bond market has overshadowed efforts by
individual countries to encourage more foreign borrowers to issue in their
domestic markets. However, this process is continuing, principally in Spain
and Japan.
For example, the European Investment Bank recently gave a significant boost
to the Matador market, Spain's domestic bond market for foreign borrowers,
by launching a Pta40bn (Dollars 315m), three-year offering, the largest
Matador to date.
In the Far East, the Asian Development Bank has pioneered efforts to
establish the 'dragon' bond market, in a bid to develop the capital markets
in Asia and stimulate participation by the region's investment community.
The ADB has launched two US-dollar dragon bonds since 1991 and earlier this
year General Electric became the first corporate borrower to tap the market,
which is targeted at non-Japanese investors in Asia.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XAZ  World.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
