<DOCNO>FT934-11951</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DJ1C4AG0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931028
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Survey of International Capital Markets (1): The good times
roll on - The economic slowdown has helped create favourable conditions for
international capital markets by encouraging governments to lower interest
rates. But the main worry is what will happen when the market turns round
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FINANCIAL institutions active in the international capital markets have
never had it so good. The fixed income businesses of many banks and
securities houses reported record first-half profits, and are on course to
post record gains for the full year.
The bull run in the world's bond markets has persisted beyond everyone's
expectations and financial markets have remained sufficiently volatile,
thanks in large part to continued machinations over the exchange rate
mechanism, to fuel derivatives business.
The economic slowdown has helped create favourable market conditions by
encouraging governments to lower interest rates. At the same time,
governments have needed to borrow more money to bridge their widening
deficits, ensuring lucrative underwriting business for financial
institutions. Underwriting revenues have also been boosted by a spate of
refinancings by companies keen to lock in the lower interest rates that have
become available.
As a result, in the US and Eurobond markets, new issue volume in the first
nine months of the year has already exceeded last year's total. In the
Eurobond market, more than Dollars 300bn of debt was issued in the first
nine months of the year, compared with Dollars 269bn last year, according to
IFR Securities Data. (These figures include an increasing number of global
bond offerings.) In the US corporate bond market, the nine-month total is
Dollars 330bn, compared with Dollars 302bn last year.
It would be hard to paint a rosier picture for investment bankers. But there
is one worry: what happens when the market turns round? The industry is
notoriously cyclical, and there are fears that on the other side of the coin
is a particularly prolonged bear market. As a result, there have been
efforts by the firms involved in the market to build up more consistent
revenue-earners such as asset management.
Still, there could be difficult times ahead. The capital markets are already
highly competitive. The new opportunities offered by the growth of
derivative markets requires substantial investment in technology and
manpower. The business requires a strong capital base at a time when capital
is in short supply.
A turnaround in the bull market could cause a shake-out of smaller players,
which have been sustained by easy trading profits during the good times. As
is the case with a growing number of industries, it is increasingly
necessary to have a global strategy to compete at the top level in the
1990s. A chasm is opening up between banks and securities houses with a
global reach and those which are effectively niche players, based in their
own domestic market, even though they may have operations overseas, or with
a single area of specialisation.
In the international capital markets, the large US houses have become
increasingly dominant. At the heart of their success has been their ability
to keep up with the rapid pace of development. The Japanese have lost ground
since the 1980s, distracted by problems in their domestic market. The
weakness of the Japanese stock market also undermined their profitable
business in Japanese equity-linked bonds, which had provided the securities
houses with a base from which to launch other businesses.
Among European houses, the big three Swiss banks have shown themselves to be
among the most internationally minded participants, and a few other European
powerhouses, such as Deutsche Bank, have also made a strong showing in the
Eurobond market. But European financial institutions have had little success
in the highly competitive US market, and a relatively small number have made
inroads into the Japanese market.
The need for a strong derivatives capacity to establish a leading position
in the international capital markets is becoming widely recognised as the
most important trend of the decade. In stock and bond markets, prices are
frequently driven by futures trading rather than by dealing in the cash
market. If financial institutions are to make markets and trade effectively
on their own accounts, they must have command of the futures markets.
Most have already reached this level of sophistication, as futures exchanges
have been on the scene, and growing in importance, for the past 20 years. A
more difficult market to enter is the highly complex and innovative
over-the-counter market in swaps and options. These products now represent a
vital service to clients, and can be highly profitable.
However, they not only require a high degree of expertise in design and
execution, they also create new risk management problems for the financial
institution concerned. The rapid growth of the market in the past five years
 -the notional amount outstanding in the market has reached Dollars 4,600bn,
according to the International Swaps and Derivatives Association - has
created concern among regulators about the potential for systemic risk to
the banking system.
The more immediate worry for some financial institutions is that they may
have left it rather late to enter the market. These days it is hard to find
any financial institution with international ambitions which does not claim
to have embraced derivatives. Yet, in practice the market is dominated by
relatively few participants.
In the battle to reach the top tier, banks and securities houses rated less
than double-A are at a competitive disadvantage, since some counterparties
refuse to deal with them. In an effort to regain this ground, several
institutions, led by Merrill Lynch, have set up separately capitalised
derivatives units, with double-A or triple-A ratings. The most recent
addition to the field is Goldman Sachs, which set up a joint venture with
Mitsui Marine and Fire Insurance earlier this month. 'The world may be
moving so that we need this to stay competitive,' said Mr Jacob Goldfield, a
Goldman partner and president of the joint venture. More financial
institutions are expected to follow suit, though some have decided to focus
on improving their own credit ratings instead.
While the steady decline in interest rates worldwide has favoured companies
and financial intermediaries, it has left investors hungry for yield, and
has created a strong impetus for investors to diversify their asset base. In
particular, US investment institutions, which have tended in the past to
concentrate on the wide range of domestic instruments available, have become
much more adventurous. According to research by management consultants
Coopers &amp; Lybrand, large US institutional investors have increased their
appetite for non-dollar products by a factor of three in the past five
years.
The appetite for yield has created strong demand for emerging market debt, a
category which covers the domestic bond markets of emerging countries and
bond offerings by borrowers from these countries in the Eurobond or other
foreign bond markets, such as the Yankee bond market. Such borrowers
generally pay a high premium, and also offer investors the possibility of
capital gains, since these borrowers are often perceived as improving
credits, so that spreads tighten, or yields fall, over time.
A similar phenomenon has occurred in the stock markets. While economic
growth in OECD countries has been sluggish, economic expansion has been
maintained in the emerging markets, which consequently offer potentially
higher gains. Again, there has been a surge of investment in domestic stock
markets and in offerings by emerging market companies in the international
market.
One area of keen interest is the developing economies of Asia, where stock
markets in Thailand and Hong Kong have been the star performers this year.
The strong economic growth in the region has also led to a rapid increase in
the amount of funds under management in the region, as well as in the need
for financing among expanding companies.
This has led to the creation of the Dragon bond market, or regional Asian
bond market, to provide a local capital market for Asian borrowers and
investors. Although it is not yet clear whether the concept will take off,
many international banks and securities houses have already built up their
trading and sales forces in Hong Kong, and to a lesser degree in Singapore.
Some have transferred certain activities from Tokyo, which remains a very
expensive business centre, to Hong Kong. Even if Asia does not become a
'fourth time zone', its financial markets are set to become increasingly
important in the next few years, particularly given the expected opening of
China to foreign investment.
While a turnaround in the bull run for bond markets could prove a setback,
there are a number of areas of expansion which will help fill the void. As
well as the continuing growth of the derivatives market and the emerging
markets, a turnaround in the bond market prompted by stronger economic
growth could also spell good news for equity markets.
</TEXT>
