<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / London Stock Exchange: Ferranti fervour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and CHRISTINE BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Speculation that a bid for troubled defence electronics group Ferranti
International may develop into a two-horse race swept through the market,
producing a rally in the shares and record volume of nearly 9 per cent of
the company's share capital.
The group said on Tuesday that it was in talks that might lead to a bid at a
penny a share. Market watchers pointed to defence electronics group GEC as
the most likely suitor, with a few suggesting French group Thomson CSF as a
possible candidate.
However, early yesterday, talk that there could be an alternative offer did
the rounds, although with no name attached to the latest speculation.
Tuesday's dramatic slump in the shares was quickly reversed and they closed
1 1/2 up at 4p, after hectic trading which saw 82m shares dealt.
Most of the selling was said to have come from the large institutions, with
short-term speculators reported to be doing the buying. Phillips &amp; Drew Fund
Management said it had sold 9m shares on Tuesday, reducing its holding to
13.71 per cent from 14.6 per cent. GEC, which has made no comment on the
rumours, rose 3 to 343p on 3.3m turnover.
</TEXT>
