<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / London Stock Exchange: Costco news hits retailers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and CHRISTINE BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEWS that Costco, the US food and retail discount group, had won its court
battle with the leading British supermarket companies to open its first
warehouse site in the UK impacted across several retail sectors yesterday.
Worst hit were the supermarket groups, which had argued in the High Court
that the US company should be treated as a retailer and not a wholesaler,
and therefore have the same regulations applied to it as other food
retailers.
After an initial strong opening, supermarket stocks tumbled as the mid-day
news came into the market. Of the groups challenging Costco in the courts,
J. Sainsbury fell 8 to 416p and Argyll 5 to 304p, while heavy trading in
Tesco saw 18m shares change hands, the price finally closing 4 1/2 down at
216p.
However, food retailing analysts said that the reaction was a symptom of
sentiment rather than a belief that the sector was under serious threat from
the new discounters. 'The food retail stocks have had a good run and some
investors are using Costco as an excuse to take profits,' was the view from
one leading salesman.
Nurdin &amp; Peacock, which intends to open its own warehouse operation under
the 'Cargo' logo, advanced strongly, although analysts pointed out that its
substantial cash and carry operations might suffer from any subsequent
expansion of companies similar to Costco. The shares added 7 at 191p.
Although many of yesterday's share falls were described as 'knee-jerk'
reactions by analysts, it was admitted that the continuing focus on
discounting in the food sector was likely to drag down sentiment in food
retailing and manufacturing. 'It underlines that margin pressure is here to
stay in both sectors,' said one food specialist.
Other sectors were also hit. Argos and Dixons weakened on fears that their
electrical appliance sales might be affected. Around half of Costco's sales
in the US are in household goods, with electrical products featuring
strongly. Argos slipped 7 to 349p and Dixons 3 to 274p.
DIY groups were also said to be affected. Ladbroke, owner of Texas Home
Care, shed 2 1/2 to 176 1/2 p. Boots fell 8 to 507p, but WH Smith, joint
owner with Boots of Do It All, firmed 2 to 492p, while Kingfisher, owner of
B&amp;Q, added 6 at 650p.
