<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Strength in car sector fails
to support Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices traded in a narrow range either side of opening values
throughout the day yesterday in the wake of a mixed batch of corporate
earnings and some positive economic news, writes Patrick Harverson in New
York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average ended 7.83 down at 3,664.66. The Standard &amp;
Poor's 500 gained 0.31 at 464.61 and the American SE composite firmed 1.42
to 475.06. The best performance came from the Nasdaq composite, which
rallied after days of heavy profit-taking to close 6.42 ahead at 771.88.
NYSE volume was 279.8m shares.
With share prices at or near record highs, investors continue to trade
cautiously, fearful of pushing stocks into previously unexplored territory
without strong backing from healthy economic or earnings fundamentals. On
the economic front, there was some good news yesterday in the form of the
September durable goods orders report.
The Commerce Department reported that orders rose 0.7 per cent last month.
Although broadly in line with economists' expectations, the figures showed
that excluding the depressed transportation component, orders actually rose
1.5 per cent in September. The data are in line with a series of recent
figures which have pointed to a gradual improvement in the pace of domestic
economic activity.
Corporate earnings news, however, was mixed, with a handful of the biggest
industrial groups in the country reporting varied performances for the third
quarter. The best showing of the day came from Ford, which announced
third-quarter net income of 79 cents a share, a sharp turnround from the
year ago 66 cents a share loss. Ford put on Dollars 5/8 at Dollars 60 1/4 in
volume of 5.1m shares, and the buying spread to other car stocks, General
Motors rising Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 46 7/8 and Chrysler Dollars  5/8 to
Dollars 55 3/8 .
While Ford prospered, other blue chip companies reported poor earnings.
Eastman Kodak posted a third-quarter loss and warned investors not to expect
record profits for 1994. The stock initially fell on the news, but rebounded
to end a net Dollars  7/8 up at Dollars 58 3/4 .
Minnesota Mining &amp; Manufacturing fell Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 103 1/2 after
revealing net income of Dollars 1.47 a share, against Dollars 1.48 earned in
the same quarter a year ago. Other big cyclical stocks were also weaker.
Canada
TORONTO set a record high in fairly busy trading as the market continued its
post-election rally. The TSE 300 index added 10.3 to close at 4,197.5. Rises
led falls by 474 to 295 after volume of 61.6m shares.
</TEXT>
