<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / World Stock Markets: Indonesian equities make a return to
favour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM KEELING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stockbrokers in Jakarta are worried about their security. Earlier this
month, riot police were called to protect the offices of Wardley James Capel
from an angry mob.
Although violent, brokers can take comfort that the incident arose from the
fact that Indonesian investors again want to own shares, and will sometimes
resort to extreme means to get them.
The market crash in 1990/91, which sent the composite index from a high of
682 points to 225, gave many Indonesians a jaundiced view of equities. Since
the start of this year, however, the index has risen by 70 per cent and,
among the IFC's emerging markets, Indonesia rates as the third best
performer in the year to date in dollar terms. Warily at first, and now with
excessive enthusiasm, local investors are returning.
Their interest has been heightened by a spate of flotations which have gone
to an instant premium to their listing price. On October 1, shares in Barito
Pacific Timber, the largest single issue this year and raising Dollars 290m,
rose 60 per cent on the first day of trading.
A few days later, more than 4,000 people turned up at the offices of Wardley
James Capel to apply for shares in Kedaung Indah Can, an enamel ware
manufacturer. Brokers expect it to open at a 50 per cent premium to its
flotation price.
Given the adage that when the public buy, a market correction is imminent,
brokers are now asking how long the good times will last.
The market looks fully valued at 23 times forecast 1993 earnings and 17
times 1994 earnings. An unwritten rule that companies coming to the market
should float at about 14 times earnings has allowed investors to make quick
gains on new issues. There are signs, however, that the rule is about to be
broken.
Ciputra Development, a leading property company, is to list next month,
raising Dollars 120m. Brokers report strong local interest, but note that
its anticipated listing price would value the company at 19 times next
year's earnings.
If other companies follow Ciputra's example and decide against listing at a
discount, the upside potential for equity investors will be limited.
Lower interest rates may improve corporate earnings, but brokers are already
assuming 20 per cent earnings growth next year. Speculation that the
government will lift the shareholding limit of 49 per cent that foreigners
may own in listed companies has also died away. The raising of the limit
would dramatically improve liquidity for foreign investors and almost
certainly drive the index higher.
The flow of foreign funds into the market, particularly from the US, should
help to sustain share prices, but Indonesia is only one of several emerging
markets in the region. With Jakarta equities looking increasingly expensive,
interest has turned to Thailand and Hong Kong.
Nevertheless, brokers say the days are gone when the market, with a
capitalisation of over Dollars 30bn, could be ignored by fund managers.
Unless there is an upset, such as the failure of a large issue or a major
corporate scandal, the market is unlikely to return to its 1992 trough.
Trading volume has doubled to above Dollars 30m a day this year and, with a
raft of new companies expected to float next year, volumes should continue
to rise.
Some investors still eye Indonesia suspiciously, recalling the scandals that
rocked the market three years ago, but many believe this year's recovery
will be sustainable.
