<PROFILE>_AN-DJ1C4AGMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931028
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Money Markets: Overnight rate hits 8%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OVERNIGHT interest rates were squeezed up to 8 per cent in the UK as an
unusually high daily liquidity shortage overhung the money markets, writes
Peter John.
Meanwhile, short-term interest rate futures were sold down on worries that
some European central banks might be becoming more wary of making further
interest rate cuts.
The UK liquidity shortage coincided with a record sized gilts auction, and
forward rates for the rest of the week suggested that tight monetary
conditions could continue today. The Bank of England initially forecast a
liquidity shortage of around Pounds 2.4bn and the estimate was later raised
to Pounds 2.5bn.
The Bank provided Pounds 785m of early assistance, followed by Pounds 278m
of assistance in the late morning and a further Pounds 698m in the
afternoon.
However, that only took Bank operations to Pounds 1.761bn and the Bank
needed to provide a further Pounds 560m of late assistance at the usual
unspecified rate, taking total help to Pounds 2.321bn.
The difficult nature of the day's trading pushed the forward rate for
today's and tomorrow's overnight money to 6.5 per cent. Dealers suggested
that banks who had the collateral necessary to take out the shortage might
have been holding their fire power for today when half of yesterday's Pounds
3.5bn gilts auction becomes payable. The problem could be compounded by
large amounts of maturing assis-tance likely to result in another high
shortage.
Meanwhile, comments by Mr Hans Tietmeyer, the head of the Bundesbank,
contributed to weakness in short-term interest rate contracts. Mr Tietmeyer
sought to damp down speculation that the recent rash of interest rate cuts
was the beginning of a trend. Euromark futures for December fell 7 basis
points to 93.81 and the equivalent French contract closed weaker at 93.63.
The short sterling December contract declined 6 basis points to 94.53.
Some dealers said the December contract was well supported at 94.50 but
others were concerned that the move reflected a fundamental change of
sentiment.
German call money was pushed up to about 6.57 per cent from about 6.5 per
cent as the Bundesbank allocated only DM66.7bn at its securities repurchase
operations and drained DM7.4bn from the system.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
