<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Survey of Locating in North America (6): The carrot and the
stick - Investment in Canada is patchy. Bernard Simon explains why
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CANADA'S investment climate these days has all the extremes - and the
in-betweens - of its weather.
At one end of the spectrum, a prolonged recession has meant that governments
at all levels are willing to pull out the stops to attract businesses which
hold out hope of creating jobs.
The slack economy has also made Canada a more attractive location for
long-term investors. Inflation and interest rates are at their lowest level
in decades. Real estate prices in most parts of the country are still in the
doldrums.
The 1989 free trade agreement with the US has reinforced pressures on
management and workers to become more competitive. Employees are willing to
do more for less, and trade unions have become more flexible.
However, these advantages do not mean that industrialists can look forward
to a warm, hassle-free welcome. Taxes are high. Non-tariff trade barriers
hamper trade between the 10 provinces, and red tape is pervasive in many
sectors, especially for any business requiring environmental clearances.
Mr Bob Brown, chairman of Price Waterhouse in Toronto, sums up the changes
in government attitudes and policies over the past year or two this way:
'The drunkard is off strong drink, but he's still into a dozen beers a day'.
The pros and cons of locating in Canada thus depend heavily on the needs and
priorities of a particular business.
Domestic and foreign investors have had little hesitation, about pouring
money into the entertainment and hospitality sectors, where the lure of
millions of well-heeled consumers is paramount.
The US National Basketball League recently received three competing bids to
set up a team in Toronto, as well as one from Vancouver. Mr David Peterson,
a former premier of Ontario, is confident that the CDollars 250m which his
group offered for the franchise will be more than recouped by sales of
tickets and souvenirs. 'The SkyDome,' Mr Peterson says, referring to
Toronto's bulbous sports stadium, 'is the one place where you find people
smiling these days.'
By contrast, the mining industry is gloomy. Tight environmental rules and
high-cost labour are causing foreign mining companies to shun Canada. Many
Canadian companies are paying more attention to exploration in Chile and
Mexico than to their own country.
Foreign investors in the politically-charged cultural industries, such as
publishing and broadcasting, also encounter strong resistance from Canadian
nationalists.
On balance, however, the climate for investment has improved rather than
deteriorated. Ms Maureen Farrow, chief economist at Coopers &amp; Lybrand in
Toronto, says that 'over the last couple of years, it's become a less risky
place.' In particular, she notes, 'our cost structure is more in line with
where it should be.'
Even the social-democratic governments in Ontario and British Columbia,
whose interventionist policies have demoralised the business community, have
shown signs of changing direction. Ontario has ordered a three-year pay
freeze for provincial civil servants. A bottom line-oriented management has
been installed at Ontario Hydro, the provincial power utility. It has
promised not to raise electricity rates next year, and to hold future rises
within cost-of-living increases.
Mr William Macdonald, a business consultant, says Canada is four to five
years into a restructuring process that could take another seven to eight
years. In a few years, he predicts, Canada could have the best possible
combination of mutually reinforcing monetary, fiscal, exchange rate and
trade policies.
Much depends however, on the political climate. While the long-term economic
outlook has improved, this week's general election has created a new set of
uncertainties.
The business community is taking comfort from the landslide victory of the
Liberals, which ended nine years of Progressive Conservative rule. The
Conservatives were devastated in the election, winning only two out of 295
seats in the House of Commons.
Today's Liberals are a far different party from the interventionist one led
by Mr Pierre Trudeau which governed in the 1970s and early 1980s. They are
more pragmatic, and more aware of the needs of both domestic and foreign
business.
The Liberals raised some fears during the election campaign that their
fiscal and monetary policies would be less disciplined than the Tories. They
also pledged to renegotiate the North American free trade agreement, which
is due to come into force on January 1 1994.
In practice, however, the policies of a Liberal government are unlikely to
be radically different from those of the Conservatives. The Liberals are
unlikely to scupper Nafta. They have also promised to give high priority to
deficit reduction.
The 1993 election will be remembered for the strong performance of two
fledgling regional parties, the separatist Bloc Quebecois in Quebec and the
Reform Party, which is based in western Canada. Both parties are generally
pro-business and favour free trade.
But the BQ's aim to take Quebec out of Canada has increased the risk of
political instability in the years ahead. The key event will be a provincial
election in Quebec, which will probably be held in the second half of 1994.
The BQ's provincial cousin, the Parti Quebecois, has promised to hold an
independence referendum within a year if it wins that election.
Ms Farrow says that the level of political risk in Canada is 'no different
to any other country these days'. But she cautions that investors would do
well to monitor developments in Quebec closely.
</TEXT>
