<PROFILE>_AN-DJ1C4AGIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931028
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Survey of Locating in North America (4): Truce sought in
bidding wars - It is costing states more and more to lure investors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS THE cost of incentives to lure new business investment has climbed to an
estimated Dollars 30bn a year, more and more US state and local officials
are wondering whether they are giving away the store.
The latest skirmish among states - for the Dollars 300m Mercedes-Benz plant
that went to Alabama - may prove to be a catalyst for a serious rethink of
these bidding wars. The size of Alabama's incentives package was regarded by
many as over the top. It included Dollars 253m upfront, plus tax breaks over
25 years that could be worth an additional Dollars 230m.
Criticism of competition for new business investment as an inefficient and
inequitable use of public resources has been building for years. As the
amount offered in incentives by US state and local governments has grown,
opposition has become louder.
One critic from a New York citizens' watchdog group has called corporate
site shopping 'polite extortion'. And Governor Jim Edgar of Illinois, a
Republican, has been insistently calling for a truce in the bidding wars by
all states.
At a National Governors' Association meeting in August, Mr Edgar made some
headway toward his goal. The organisation issued a policy statement to the
effect that competition among states for investment should not be ruled by
how much a state sweetens the deal for a single investor, but by how much
the deal can improve the state's general business climate.
The competition should be judged on education, transportation, tele-
communications, tax policies, business regulation and fiscal stability, the
governors said.
Notably, they also agreed that they had the right to consult whenever they
believed a company was trying to play them off against one another to win
bigger concessions. They warned, too, that governors should be prepared to
take the political heat that might result if they declined to engage in a
bidding war for a high-impact, high-profile project.
While all these seem noble goals, Mr Jay Kayne, policy studies director for
the National Governors' Association, says that the governors do not
realistically expect a quick halt to high-cost bidding. The competition for
Mercedes, for instance, had already reached a fever pitch. But they do hope
to spur some states to at least review their incentive policies. The NGA has
been trying to meet top corporate leaders to win their co-operation.
The slow growth of the US economy has been blamed for pushing up the cost of
incentives. With fewer big investment projects on offer, states that are in
desperate need of jobs feel compelled to bid up their hand-outs to
companies. 'It's market forces,' says Mr Kayne.
Moreover, in cases involving big, high-profile investors, Mr Kayne likens a
state's pursuit of a project to the development of a shopping mall. 'If you
get the Sears or the Macy's in there, then other stores will want to come
in.'
The consequences of reckless bidding are, however, becoming more punishing.
In 1991, for example, Indianapolis won the bidding for a United Airlines
maintenance facility by contributing a large chunk of the Dollars 1bn or so
that Indiana could give away. But in the process, the city put itself deeply
in the red.
The doubts about fat packages of incentives have been heightened by surveys
of company executives which show that these hand-outs often do not in
themselves sway corporate decisions on site locations. If contenders offer
approximately the same proximity to markets and materials, good
transportation and infrastructure and availability of labour, incentives
amount to little more than a thick layer of icing on the cake for some
companies.
As the mood on incentives has soured, a backlash has been rising against
companies that do not fulfil their promises, particularly on job creation.
States have increasingly placed 'clawback' provisions in their deals,
requiring that subsidies be returned if a company's promises are not
fulfilled.
However, PHH Fantus, the leading corporate relocation adviser, says that its
clients rarely accept such conditions and they are negotiated out of a deal.
Nonetheless, a number of law suits have been filed on the basis of a
company's failure to deliver on its promises. One of the better known ones
is that of the Ypsilanti Township, in Michigan, against General Motors.
GM's Willow Run assembly plant, located in Ypsilanti, was chosen to be
closed in early 1992, violating what the township said was the company's
promises of jobs and investment in return for tax abatements.
The township won its case in the first trial, but lost an appeal by GM in
the Michigan Court of Appeals. The state's Supreme Court then refused to
hear the case, but the township is still pursuing an aspect of its case
further.
While its previous action would have forced GM to fulfil promises on jobs
and keep the plant open, its current tack is to press a claim of 'unjust
enrichment' against GM and win back money that the company saved from
Ypsilanti's tax abatements.
Cases such as this have given pause to both sides in negotiations for site
locations. They also have contributed to a new sobriety among state and
local officials in their approaches to new investors.
Yet, while the need for job-creating investment is still pressing, the US is
unlikely to see the end of these bidding wars - as the scramble to secure
the Mercedes-Benz site clearly shows.
