<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Survey of Locating in North America (2): It is nice to feel
really wanted - Why Mercedes came to Alabama
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALABAMA'S slogan is the 'state of surprises'. It certainly lived up to it in
late September when Mercedes-Benz, the German vehicle manufacturer,
announced it had chosen Tuscaloosa, Alabama, as the site of its first car
manufacturing plant outside Germany.
Although Alabama was known to be on Mercedes' shortlist of US states, it was
not thought to be among the front-runners. So how was Alabama selected?
When Mercedes announced last April that it planned to build a Dollars 300m
plant in the US to produce a new four-wheel drive sports utility vehicle, it
set up a site selection team - advised by Fluor Daniels, a California-based
engineering and construction firm - and was inundated with offers from more
than 30 states.
Members of the team first made incognito investigations of the various
states and their offerings. 'We wanted to begin the process with a more
factual evaluation, leaving out all emotional or political aspects,' says Mr
Dieter Zetsche, a senior Mercedes official.
Criteria such as transport costs, quality of the workforce and proposals
from government agencies narrowed the field down to 150 sites in 30 states.
Further criteria, such as distance to nearby residential areas or existing
automotive operations, reduced the tally to 64 sites in 21 states.
That was followed by studies on infrastructure, education and availability
of the workforce, as well as productivity, which brought the number down to
11 states and 20 sites.
Further analysis of such factors as distance to suppliers, training
programmes and quality to life left Mercedes with six sites in six states:
Tennessee, Nebraska, South Carolina, North Carolina, Georgia and Alabama.
'At this point,' says Mr Zetsche, 'we visited the remaining sites
repeatedly, toured the universities and colleges, visited companies,
evaluated the business climate, intensified our investigation of the
workforce, elaborated differences in operating costs and investment costs,
and ended up with three final sites.' These were in North Carolina, South
Carolina and Alabama.
It is not surprising that all three short-listed sites, and five of the
final six, should be in the south-eastern US. It has become a Mecca for
foreign companies over the past two decades, thanks to its relatively cheap
but skilled and abundant labour force, anti-union tradition, affordable
housing, attractive life-style, good transport links with Europe - and
governments willing to throw money at companies to locate in their states.
The Carolinas, in particular, have become a haven for German companies, and
BMW, the luxury carmaker, is in the process of building its first US plant
in South Carolina.
Alabama has in the past lagged other south-east rivals in attracting
high-profile capital investments like this, partly because the state showed
less entrepreneurial drive and partly because of its old, lingering image as
a haven for boorish 'rednecks' and its history of racism and police
brutality in the civil rights era of the 1950s and 1960s.
It was disappointed when two of the biggest new vehicle industry projects of
the 1980s - Nissan's US plant and General Motors' new Saturn works - were
won by its northern neighbour, Tennessee.
The state was lucky in that Mercedes' search for a plant, which began in
April, coincided with the appointment of a new governor, Mr Jim Folsom, who
replaced Mr Guy Hunt after he was forced from office in a theft scandal.
Mr Folsom, anxious to prove himself, poured immense energy into the Mercedes
project, and made a key appointment in putting Mr Billy Joe Camp, a state
government veteran, at the head of the state development office and in
charge of negotiations with Mercedes.
Mercedes restricted the state teams it was negotiating with to two people,
which threw a lot of pressure on Mr Camp and a colleague. The two spent long
hours refining the state's offer of incentives - right down to details of
how many four-wheel drive vehicles were in the Alabama government fleet, and
how many it could therefore be expected to buy from the Mercedes plant.
The states did not know precisely what the others were offering. Mercedes
was anxious not to conduct a bidding war between them. Mr Andreas Renschler,
who heads the sports utility project, says the company wanted to see what
each state believed it could bring to the partnership.
Alabama ended up offering a very generous package of incentives, totalling
Dollars 253m, including Dollars 17.4m to buy the plant site for Mercedes and
develop it, Dollars 42.6m for building construction and Dollars 30m for a
training centre. It will also pay Dollars 60m to train Mercedes workers and
Dollars 77m to develop the related infrastructure, such as roads and water
lines.
On top of all that, Mercedes qualifies for tax breaks related to its profits
and head count. These could total up to Dollars 9.2m a year for up to 25
years.
Unsuccessful states have grumbled that Alabama paid over the odds, but
Mercedes insists that the offerings from rival states were essentially the
same and these were not the most important factor in its decision.
Mr Renschler says that its US plant commitment is so important for Mercedes
that 'it is not a question of incentives. They are always a short-term
thing. We want to build cars here for the next 20 years.'
So what tipped the deal Alabama's way? The University of Alabama at
Tuscaloosa, which will play a big role in worker training, could have been
significant. The vehicle industry in neighbouring Tennessee was also a
factor.
The quality of the local infrastructure played a role, though Mercedes has
yet to decide whether it will export through the ports of Mobile (Alabama),
Jacksonville (Florida) or Charleston (South Carolina). The local quality of
life is also pleasant. Tuscaloosa is a small, rather sleepy city, while
Birmingham, 50 miles away, offers big city attractions and shopping malls.
Still, the other sites on the Mercedes shortlist had all these attractions
as well, and arguably better infrastructure links. In the end, what may have
swung it for Alabama was a 'gut feeling' on the part of Mercedes team that
this was the right location.
That, in turn, seems to have stemmed in part from the sheer zeal with which
Alabama pursued Mercedes. It is nice to feel really wanted, in a state so
desperate for a big project that you will be treated like royalty - as
befits the Mercedes image.
</TEXT>
