<PROFILE>_AN-DJ1C4AGEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931028
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Survey of Locating in North America (1): Beat of the
heartlands - For those European and Japanese companies which want to
establish a global presence, North America still beckons. The lion's share
of recent investment has gone to the south-eastern US and the Rocky Mountain
region
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
First: BMW. Now: Mercedes-Benz. Over the past 15 months each of these luxury
car manufacturers has decided to locate its first manufacturing plant
outside Germany in the US - underscoring the continued importance of North
America as a centre for European and Japanese companies aspiring to a global
presence.
From April, when Mercedes announced its intention to come to North America,
states across the US have become involved in a six-month tug of war to get
the company to choose them as the site of its plant.
In September, Alabama emerged as the surprise winner of the contest - a
choice which says much about the factors that companies weigh up when
deciding precisely where in North America they need to locate.
Alabama is in the south-eastern US, as are five of the six states which
appeared on Mercedes' shortlist. This region has attracted particularly
strong European investment - especially from Germany. So strong is the
German presence in North and South Carolina that parts of the main highway
through the region, Interstate 85, have been dubbed the 'autobahn'.
BMW, for its part, decided last year to site its US plant in South Carolina
 -one of the states on the Mercedes shortlist.
European and American companies like the region because it has low labour
costs compared with the traditional manufacturing 'rustbelt' states of the
north; a strong tradition of hostility to unions; a low cost of living; easy
access to ports for the export market; a large labour pool and good
universities; and state governments willing to lure companies with huge
incentives for site purchase and worker training. Alabama's package for
Mercedes is valued at over Dollars 250m.
However, the south-east is far from being the only US region profiting from
corporate location decisions. For example, the Rocky Mountain region has
become the fastest-growing area of America, apparently attracting jobs and
people from California, which is suffering from a severe recession, a
deteriorating quality of life and heavy state regulation of industry.
Mr David Hale, chief economist at Kemper Financial Services, points out
that, in terms of growth, 'many states in the heartland of America are now
performing significantly better than they did during the early 1980s, while
states in the north-east as well as California are underperforming'.
Foreign direct investment in the US grew remarkably in the 1980s. This was
partly through the start-up of greenfield plants, notably from Japanese car
manufacturers, but much more so through the takeover of existing US
companies. Direct foreign investment grew from Dollars 83bn in 1980 to
Dollars 403.7bn in 1990.
Since then, however, foreign spending on acquiring or establishing US
businesses has fallen sharply. In 1992 it totalled Dollars 13.5bn, down 47
per cent on the previous year and the fourth consecutive year of decline. It
was the lowest total since the Dollars 8.09bn recorded in 1983.
When disinvestment by foreign companies is added in, foreigners took out
Dollars 3.9bn of direct investment more than they put into the US in 1992 -
the first such outflow in decades.
Several factors appear to lie behind this. First, global recession
restrained investors' ability to pump capital into new foreign ventures
around the world - not just in the US.
The Commerce Department also speculates that investment funds may have been
diverted from the US by increased economic integration in the European
Community and the new business opportunities opening up in eastern Europe.
Other factors may have been rapid economic growth in parts of south-east
Asia and an improved investment climate in parts of Latin America.
And while the US seems this year to be once more in the throes of a takeover
boom, after four years of quiet, foreign companies are not yet particularly
prominent in this wave.
That is because many of the new bids involve industries which are either
distinctly domestic in nature, such as health care or regional banking, or
have limits on foreign participation. US regulations limit foreign companies
to owning 20 per cent of most large companies in telecommunications - a
sector at the start of a dramatic wave of consolidation.
However, foreign investment may also have been discouraged by a feeling that
the US has become less welcoming in recent years. For example, considerable
anti-foreign sentiment was stirred up during the takeover wave of the 1980s,
when jingoistic Americans complained that Japanese and European companies
were acquiring some of the nation's 'crown jewels'.
The edginess has been compounded by the ambiguous attitude towards foreign
investment of the Clinton administration. Mr Ian Martin, a leading executive
at the British food and drinks group Grand Metropolitan, called last summer
for a 'official US assurance that all members of the business community,
foreign and domestic, will have access to the so-called level playing field
 -that they can count on even-handed enforcement of laws pertaining to basic
business operation, investment and taxation'.
The foreign community has been particularly concerned by Mr Clinton's
approach to the long-running unitary taxation court case which pits
Britain's Barclays Bank against the state of California.
This involves California's policy of taxing subsidiaries of foreign-based
multinationals on a proportion of the worldwide income of the parent company
and affiliates. For years, the federal government said California's unusual
approach was unconstitutional and inconsistent with federal tax policy, but
during last year's presidential election campaign Mr Clinton pledged to take
the state's side.
Last month, California made it far easier for him to do that, without
abandoning the government's long-held position, when it passed a law which
addressed most of the foreign companies' complaints.
Nevertheless, Mr Clinton has now raised hackles by urging the Supreme Court
to deny an appeal from Barclays that challenges the original judgment made
against it by a California court. The White House argues that the recent
change in Californian law makes a hearing unnecessary.
However, as much as Dollars 900m in back taxes and interest is at stake for
California in this case and similar ones filed by other foreign companies.
Mr Clinton also provoked foreign corporate concern during the election
campaign with proposals to raise Dollars 45bn from multinationals in
additional taxes.
Still, tax experts reckon that the budget package finally approved by
Congress in August means the total will be only Dollars 800m, about half of
which will come from stricter enforcement of transfer pricing rules and half
from tightening of rules covering so-called 'earnings stripping', limiting
tax deductions for interest payments to a foreign party.
Despite these niggles, the US market is likely to re-emerge as extremely
attractive for foreign investment in the second half of this decade as the
global economy recovers.
Mercedes and BMW, for example, could have sited their plants anywhere in the
world. They chose the US for its combination of reasonable labour costs
(some 30 per cent below Germany), skilled labour force, and the largest and
most competitive vehicle market in the globe.
The potential will be even larger if the proposed North American Free Trade
Agreement, setting up a free trade area between the US, Canada and Mexico,
comes into being, creating a market of some 365m consumers.
However, the Nafta accord is in serious difficulties in the US Congress,
which will vote on the issue shortly, and is under fire from the influential
Mr Ross Perot, the Texan who stood last year as an independent presidential
candidate and warns of a 'giant sucking sound' of American jobs heading for
Mexico.
</TEXT>
