<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: EC to provide funds for CIS
metal industries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
European Commission officials said yesterday the EC would be providing funds
to help the non-ferrous metals industries of the Commonwealth of Independent
States, including the aluminium industry, to make market studies and for
retraining, writes Kenneth Gooding, Mining Correspondent. They said the
community still hoped to reach agreement with the CIS aluminium industry
before the end of November, when the present import restrictions end.
The European Aluminium Association said it was poised to assist the CIS in
refurbishing and updating its 14 aluminium smelters, especially with
environmental technology. Its quarterly report yesterday pointed out that
'the emission of hazardous substances is eight to 10 times higher than
European regulations allow and sooner rather than later the CIS will be
forced to tackle the question of the environment'.
The European industry was also ready to help stimulate consumption of
aluminium in the CIS. If consumption improved from 5kg to 10kg per head of
population - 'a realistic scenario if the conversion to a market-oriented
economy is successful' - private consumption would double to 3m tonnes a
year, 500,000 tonnes more than the total amount of CIS aluminium estimated
to have arrived in the EC in 1992.
Meanwhile, the US Aluminium Association said yesterday the US government had
responded well to its calls for help and 'seems to understand the urgency of
resolving this issue'. At the invitation of Russia, last week the US, the EC
and four other aluminium-producing countries met in Moscow for the first
multilateral talks about the issue. The countries will meet again in
Washington in December. Mr David Parker, president of the association, said:
'This is a situation that traditional market forces alone cannot correct.'
</TEXT>
