<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Oversupply makes forest
thinning uneconomic
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WEAK DEMAND, oversupply and falling prices for pulpwood and other
small-sized wood have made forest thinning operations uneconomic in many
areas of Europe, with damaging social and environmental consequences,
according to two United Nations agencies.
In a joint statement, the Rome-based Food and Agriculture Organisation and
the Economic Commission for Europe, which has its headquarters in Geneva,
warn that in many countries there is a serious risk of a reduction in 'the
forest's stability, vitality, productivity and its contribution to the rural
economy and society'.
Paradoxically, the statement puts the blame for this situation largely on a
supposedly environment-friendly development, the big increase in the
recycling of used paper in Europe. The two organisations call for the
development of new outlets for small-sized wood, including its use as an
energy source, and the possible use of waste paper as fuel to free up the
paper market for pulpwood.
Reporting on market developments for forest products in 1993 and prospects
for 1994, the ECE notes that prices for pulp are at their lowest level for
many years and that many mills are running well below capacity. Apart from
more use of waste paper, this reflects overcapacity in the pulp sector and
production of higher grades leading to a higher proportion of coatings and
fillers, the ECE says.
At the same time, pulpwood is being imported into the European market,
mainly by Finland and Sweden. The report says markets for pulpwood are
increasingly being internationalised as large importers draw supplies from a
wide range of sources which compete against each other.
More generally, the ECE report shows that European markets for forest
products have remained marked by weak demand and strong competition on
increasingly global markets. In North America markets were stronger and
prices rose. For countries moving to market economy systems, 1993 saw steep
drops in demand for forest products combined with supply bottlenecks. The
outlook for eastern Europe remains sombre.
The ECE says almost no quantitative information is available for Russia 'due
to the complete breakdown of the state information system'. However, the
report expects Russian sawn softwood exports to fall by 25 per cent in 1993
and then to remain constant at around 5m cubic metres due to supply
constraints.
