<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / International Company News: Telmex climbs 15% in quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TELEFONOS de Mexico (Telmex), Mexico's largest private company, reported net
profits of 2.38bn new pesos (Dollars 765m) in the third quarter, a 15.3 per
cent increase in real terms over the same period last year.
Telmex benefited from a strong gain in local and long distance telephone
traffic in the third quarter, despite Mexico's sluggish economic growth.
Local revenues rose in real terms by 12.1 per cent compared with the third
quarter last year, long distance revenues by 9.3 per cent, and international
revenues by 5.1 per cent.
The monopoly telephone company installed 194,000 new lines in the quarter,
bringing the total in service to 7,276,528. New line installation is running
slightly ahead of the 12 per cent growth required under the government
concession.
Operating profits rose by a more modest 3.5 per cent in the quarter after a
37.8 per cent advance in operating and maintenance expenses. The increase in
costs pushed margins down to 42.8 per cent from 45.6 per cent in the third
quarter last year, according to Baring Securities.
Telmex said costs rose largely because of its programme of renovating
outside cables, replacing obsolete equipment and substituting analog with
digital lines. It said there were additional third-quarter costs from
training its workforce.
Telcel, the cellular subsidiary, which faces tougher competition after Bell
Atlantic took a stake in the rival company Iusacell, increased subscribers
to 193,851.
This was just 2,547 more subscribers than in the second quarter, suggesting
that the phenomenal growth of the company in past three years is coming to
an end.
</TEXT>
