<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / International Company News: Complex call for Dutch telecoms
 -The tough task presented by the KPN sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WITH tens of millions of 'customer contacts' per day, Koninklijke PTT
Nederland (KPN), the Dutch telecommunications and postal company, ought to
be the quintessential household name, auguring well for its partial
privatisation early next year.
The flotation is the biggest in the history of the Amsterdam bourse, and is
a formidable marketing challenge for all banks, brokers and advisers
involved.
The timing of KPN's initial flotation, however, gives it a lead over its
larger European rivals - like Deutsche Telekom (DT) - in the competition for
investors' funds. DT is likely to be two years behind.
But the inclusion of the Dutch postal services in the flotation sets KPN
apart from the string of privatisations awaiting the European
telecommunications sector.
International investors will have to be convinced that, contrary to the
situation in most other countries, the Netherlands' postal operations are
profitable and achieving roughly the same return on investment as KPN's
telecommunications side.
At home, marketing the shares will also be far from simple. Though every
potential Dutch investor is almost by definition a KPN customer, he or she
may not immediately recognise the company's name. It is KPN's two main
operating subsidiaries - PTT Post and PTT Telecom - which are household
names. KPN itself is a holding company, the name of which commands little
recognition.
A first tranche of shares in KPN, representing up to 30 per cent of the
company's 40m shares, is scheduled to be floated in the first six months of
1994. Estimates for the total value of KPN vary widely from Fl 16bn (Dollars
8.6bn) to as much as Fl 28bn, making the first tranche worth at least Fl
5bn. Additional tranches are expected to reduce the state's stake to around
one third later in the 1990s.
Oyens &amp; Van Eeghen, an Amsterdam-based subsidiary of Credit Lyonnais,
estimates that the shares of Fl 100 nominal will be floated at Fl 425 each,
valuing the company as a whole at Fl 17bn. It also believes KPN will carry
out a 10-for-one share split before the flotation to boost the marketability
of the shares.
In London, Robert Fleming Securities puts the probable range at between Fl
425 and Fl 600 per share and says the shares would be particularly
attractive towards the bottom end of this range.
Definitive forecasts are complicated by the fact that KPN has yet to comment
on its future dividend policy. As a utility stock, KPN is likely to be
regarded as an investment for income rather than for capital growth.
The Dutch government is setting the machinery in place for the
privatisation. Earlier this month it chose ABN-Amro, the Dutch bank, as
global co-ordinator for the share flotation, with ING and Rabobank as
co-lead managers of the syndicate in the Netherlands. The names of banks
leading foreign syndicates are expected to be disclosed later this autumn.
In the summer, the government made clear what kind of domestic competition
PTT Telecom can expect to face in its home market later this decade.
Starting in 1995, the country's railway, cable television operators and
electrical utilities will be encouraged to join forces and lease their lines
and cables to business customers. In turn, these corporate customers will be
able to use these lines for data communication and private networks between
their offices. In 1998, these lines can also be used for normal 'voice'
services.
Despite this looming increase in competition, KPN is expected to continue
its dominance of the Dutch telecom market.
Apart from the flotation price, one of the most intriguing unknowns is the
way the government will choose to pitch the shares to the public.
Unlike Britain, which under recent Conservative governments has consciously
tried to widen share ownership, the Netherlands has never sought to promote
share buying among the public. Nor does the country have a tradition of big
privatisations - because it never went in for mass nationalisation in the
first place.
In the late 1980s, during the sale of two tranches of shares in DSM, the
Dutch chemicals group, no special effort was made to attract private
investors.
This time, the sale of a company with far stronger roots in Dutch society
may spur the government into at least considering the use of special
promotions to sell the shares.
So far, there seems to be little support for the idea of offering
shareholders discounts on their telephone bills. But one idea is a scheme
under which small investors will pay reduced commission charges when buying
KPN shares.
This is the third in a series on the privatisation of Europe's state
telecommunications operators. Earlier articles appeared on October 11 and
26; the next appears on November 4.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                     KPN'S FOUR-YEAR RECORD
                      Year-end December 31
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                                      1989    1990    1991    1992
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Net turnover (Fl m)                 12,741  13,569  14,480  15,622
Year on Year increase %                 NA     6.5     6.7     7.9
Operating results (Fl m)             2,812   2,927   2,895   3,101
Return on average total Capital (%)   11.8    11.8    11.2    11.7
Profit after taxation (Fl m)         1,479   1,574   1,609   1,664
Return on average group equity (%)    17.6    16.8    15.6    14.8
EPS (Fl)                             36.98   39.35   40.23   41.60
