<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / International Company News: Union Carbide held back in
quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNION Carbide's profit recovery remained stalled in the third quarter as the
weak international economy and overcapacity continued to hold down demand
for its main chemical products.
The company, which three months ago said it was stepping up the pace of a
three-year old cost-cutting programme, recorded net income of Dollars 36m,
or 23 cents a share.
Although an improvement on the Dollars 20m, or 14 cents a share, in the same
period in 1992, the figure was down from Dollars 41m, or 14 cents a share,
in the second three months of this year.
Union Carbide also announced an organisational shake-up yesterday, scrapping
its four operating divisions and creating nine new business units which will
each report directly to Mr William Joyce, president and chief operating
officer.
'Fewer layers of management and staff consolidation will help us reduce
costs and speed up strategic and operations decision-making in our
businesses,' said Mr Robert Kennedy, chairman and chief executive.
Sales volumes had fallen 5 per cent in the third quarter compared with the
previous three months, said Mr Kennedy.
'Prices for our most cyclical products - polyester glycol, antifreeze glycol
and polyethylene - remain at historic low levels,' he added. Sales in the
quarter, at Dollars 1.13bn, were down from Dollars 1.24bn previously.
A Dollars 30m after-tax gain from the sale of the company's organo-silicon
business was wiped out by a Dollars 30m after-tax charge from the shutdown
of a manufacturing plant in Canada.
Akzo, the Dutch group, and AlliedSignal of the US have agreed to set up a
joint European carpet fibre venture, Reuters reports. Under the previously
announced deal the two companies will bring their European interests
together in a new company which will be majority owned and managed by
AlliedSignal.
</TEXT>
