<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / International Company News: Bethlehem Steel back in black
after three years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BETHLEHEM Steel, the US's second largest producer, recorded its first
quarterly profit in three years as the effects of cost-cutting and this
year's steel price rises took effect.
At the same time Mr Hank Barnette, chairman, indicated a continuation of the
recovery, pointing to a 'moderate recovery' in the economy and most of the
company's markets.
'Orders for light flat rolled products remain at moderately strong levels,'
he added.
Bethlehem recorded net income of Dollars 31m, or 23 cents a share, in the
third quarter, compared with a Dollars 58m loss the year before, on sales up
5 per cent to nearly Dollars 1.1bn. Operating costs fell 10 per cent, to
Dollars 926m.
The latest figures are flattered by a one-off tax benefit of Dollars 25m.
