<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / International Company News: A game of not-so-happy families
 -A dispute at a top Indian tyre manufacturer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LEADING Indian businessman has turned to the courts in a long-running
battle with his son for control of his flagship company.
Mr Raunaq Singh, who is 71, is fighting his eldest son, Mr Onkar Kanwar, for
control of Apollo Tyres, a top tyre manufacturer, founded by Mr Singh.
Mr Singh, company chairman, this week filed a suit in the Delhi High Court
to block a recent bid by the Apollo board to transfer some of hisexecutive
powers to Mr Kanwar, who is managing director.
The dispute at Apollo is one of a spate of family rows which have recently
erupted at family-owned Indian groups. Such arguments are not unusual since
families generally hold wealth in common, creating many opportunities for
squabbles between fathers and their sons and heirs.
However, the onset of economic liberalisation has added a sense of urgency
to these quarrels because increasing competition is forcing companies to
make difficult decisions rapidly.
Mr Singh has taken his fight into the open and hired a high-profile lawyer -
Mr P. Chidambaram, a former commerce minister - to plead his case. Mr Singh
said yesterday: 'I'm a self-made man. My son has been misbehaving. I have to
deal with it.'
Mr Kanwar has limited his public comments to conciliatory remarks. His staff
said he was unavailable for comment yesterday.
The dispute dates back to the mid-1980s when Mr Singh became increasingly
active in business organisations. He served as president for the Federation
of Indian Chambers of Commerce and Industry.
Day-to-day control of Apollo passed to Mr Kanwar, who turned a poorly
performing company into the biggest profit-earner in the Indian tyre
industry.
Under his de facto leadership sales grew from Rs1.46bn (Dollars 46m) in 1987
to Rs5.1bn in the year to March 1993, while net profits jumped from almost
nothing to R210m. Mr Singh was not unhappy with his eldest son's performance
but, with four other sons' futures to consider, he tried to reassert his
authority. The dispute became so bitter that managers and directors
representing institutional shareholders became increasingly involved in
trying to keep the peace between father and son.
The family jointly holds about 19 per cent of the equity; the rest is held
by outside shareholders.
The institutions have quietly sided with Mr Kanwar, whom they respect for
his business skill and his strategy of focusing on tyres instead of
diversifying into other industries. Mr Singh favours diversification - the
traditional strategy of Indian business families.
Mr Singh has gone to great lengths to try and turn opinion in his favour.
This summer, he accused Mr Kanwar of infringing the Companies Act and
engaging in questionable financial dealings including making a Rs5m loan to
Mr Harshad Mehta, the stockbroker at the centre of last year's Bombay
securities market scandal. Mr Kanwar denied the claims.
Matters came to a head after a board meeting on September 10.
Although the meeting began with Mr Singh in the chair and Mr Kanwar present,
both men agreed to withdraw when the discussion moved to dividing
responsibilities between father and son.
The directors agreed to vest formally day-to-day control of the company in
Mr Kanwar's hands, including powers over all Apollo's bank dealings. Mr
Singh was given charge of 'diversification'.
When he saw the minutes, Mr Singh said responsibility for 'diversification'
was a 'mockery' in a company which his son was committed to not
diversifying.
In his suit, Mr Singh calls on the court to scrap the decisions the board
took in his absence and postpone the next board meeting, due on Friday,
until the matter is resolved.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Apollo Tyres.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>INZ  India, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3011 Tires and Inner Tubes.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>PEOP  People.
    COMP  Shareholding.
</TP>
