<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / International Company News: Moody's reviews local rating of
Hong Kong's Mass Transit group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HONG KONG'S Mass Transit Railway Corporation (MTRC) is having its local
credit rating reviewed by Moody's Investors Service as a result of concerns
over Hong Kong's rapid economic and political integration with China.
The announcement comes at a sensitive time for MTRC, which plans to raise
substantial external funding for the HKDollars 33bn (USDollars 4.2bn) rail
link between Hong Kong island and Chek Lap Kok airport, assuming it can
secure approval from China.
Moody's comments on the potential down-grading of MTRC's Aa2 rating for Hong
Kong dollar-denominated debt made no reference to the financial position of
the company. They referred only to the impact of 'Hong Kong's accelerated
pace of integration into China' on financial and monetary trends in the
colony.
Mr Roger Moss, finance director of MTRC, said he believed the announcement
would have little impact on the corporation's ability to raise capital.
MTRC - which is owned by the Hong Kong Government - has just returned from a
US roadshow. Mr Moss said it was apparent that the group could get ready
access to low-cost financing outside, regardless of the rating for its local
debt.
Of greater concern is the implication of the current political talks between
Britain and China on Hong Kong's political future; worsening relations
between the two sides have been primarily responsible for the lengthy
postponement of approval for the MTRC's newest rail project.
However, an adverse decision by Moody's would be expected to have an impact
on the ability of other Hong Kong companies to access cheap funding in the
overseas capital markets.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Mass Transit Railway Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
