<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / International Company News: Tokai Bank cuts pre-tax profit
forecast to Y12bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TOKAI Bank, the Japanese commercial bank, yesterday halved its pre-tax
profit forecast to Y12bn (Dollars 113.2m) for the first half to the end of
September, saying that an expected increase in banking profits would be
undermined by write-offs of non-performing loans.
Along with other Japanese banks, Tokai has been able to increase core
earnings as falling interest rates have created a favourable spread. It is
taking the opportunity to write off and make provision for losses arising
from lending during the 'bubble era' of the late 1980s.
Mr Shuichi Midorikawa, assistant general manager, said the bank had seen
'large profits' from arbitrage trading in London.
However, he said that these would 'have little effect' on first-half
results, which would be more determined by the 'profitability of our loan
portfolio'.
At the end of March, Nagoya-based Tokai reported that its non-performing
loans were Y828bn, and that figure is expected to have increased over the
first half. Mr Midorikawa said the write-off figure for the first half had
not been finalised.
'We hope to do as much as possible,' he said. Regardless of the write-offs
and provisions, the bank expects that net income will be 4.5 per cent above
the previously forecast Y11bn.
In the first half last year, Tokai reported a pre-tax profit of Y28.4bn, and
a net profit of Y13.5bn on total income of Y972.9bn, which the bank expects
will fall to Y902bn for the period just ended.
Japanese banks are expected to face a difficult second half. They have
already absorbed many of the benefits of falling interest rates, but are
still confronted by an increase in problem loans and weak demand from
corporate customers, who are lowering their capital spending targets.
</TEXT>
