<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / International Company News: Rhone-Poulenc sell-off launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE FRENCH Government yesterday launched its second big privatisation,
announcing that investors could start reserving shares in Rhone-Poulenc, the
chemicals group from today. The sale of the government's 43 per cent stake
should take place within the next few weeks.
Mr Edmond Alphandery, the economy minister, said that the successful
privatisation of Banque National de Paris earlier this month augured well
for the sale of Rhone-Poulenc. The public offer for BNP was more than five
times subscribed and the institutional tranche was more than 12 times
subscribed.
The Rhone-Poulenc issue, which is expected to raise FFr15bn-FFr16bn (Dollars
2.7bn-Dollars 2.9bn), is aimed at individual investors. Of the 79.3m shares
that the government will sell, 47.6m will go to a public share offering for
French and EC citizens and there will be a placement of 31.7m shares for
French and international institutional investors.
The public share offering will last for six trading days after the price is
set. Private investors subscribing to the public offer will be given
priority for up to 60 shares each. If they pay for their shares through the
conversion of Balladur bonds, a government bond issue launched in the
summer, they will have priority for a further 60 shares.
Analysts predicted a smooth sale of the Rhone-Poulenc stake. It is a much
smaller operation than BNP, which raised FFr34bn, and the chemicals group
has been partially privatised through a series of share placings, the most
recent of which was in January.
'It is unlikely to be as much as a giveaway as BNP,' said an analyst, 'But
it it will probably be attractively priced.'
</TEXT>
