<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / International Company News: RWE lifted by turnover growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ESSEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RWE, Germany's largest energy company, managed to increase net profits by
DM1m to DM1.05bn (Dollars 655m) in the year ending June 3 after a 2.6 per
cent rise in net sales to DM53.1bn.
Mr Friedhelm Gieske, chairman, said the growth in sales was largely due to
the inclusion of east German companies, including petrol stations run by
DEA, the petroleum products division, in the consolidated accounts. Without
them turnover growth would have been restrained to 0.4 per cent. The
dividend will remain at DM12.
Turnover in RWE's energy division was 0.6 per cent down on the previous
year, caused by a cyclical decline of the group's electricity sales volume
by 3 per cent, but there was a rise of 4.7 per cent in gas sales. Mr Gieske
said increases in labour and personnel costs 'are increasingly creating
problems for the energy division'.
He said that it was time to consider a change in the price structures for
its electricity customers, who, he said, 'were paying 23 per cent less for
energy than eight years ago'. RWE had kept electricity prices stable since
1986 and had lowered them by about 5 per cent in 1990, the chairman added.
Sales of Rheinbraun, the brown coal division, increased to DM2.32bn from
DM1.69bn. But Mr Gieske explained that the turnover of 37.6 per cent
included east German fuel trading companies. Otherwise, Rheinbraun's
turnover would have increased by 7.4 per cent on the previous year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Rheinisch Westfalisches Elektrizitatswerk.
</CO>
