<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / UK Company News: On-site contractor behind AAF's fall to
Pounds 11m loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AAF INDUSTRIES, the mini-conglomerate which issued two profits warnings in
quick succession after a rights issue in April this year, yesterday reported
interim pre-tax losses of Pounds 10.98m compared with profits of Pounds
2.26m.
The losses stemmed directly from expansion of AAF's prefabricated building
manufacturing business, which it bought in 1989, into an on-site contractor.
This business had operating losses of Pounds 10.8m in the six months to June
30. The group will also incur an additional Pounds 7m cost in the second
half following the decision to close this business and transfer some of the
manufacturing activities to Brandesburton.
On April 1, AAF announced a 1-for-4 rights issue at 175p which was 97.6 per
cent subscribed. Three months later the group made its first profits
warning, followed by a second in September.
The sudden fall in the company's fortunes will embarrass Hambro Magan, its
merchant bankers, but also KPMG, the auditors.
AAF said yesterday that the task of establishing the financial position of
the Blackburn business was made more difficult partly because of 'incomplete
accounting records'.
Investors and the company will question whether any of the costing
procedures or management controls were already inadequate at the time KPMG
signed off on last year's accounts.
They will also be concerned that KPMG will have revisited AAF ahead of the
April rights and apparently found nothing amiss.
AAF said its debt at the half year had risen from Pounds 18.6m to Pounds
21.97m and had risen substantially since.
W&amp;A Investment Corp, the South African company that controls 43 per cent of
AAF, has guaranteed and provided funding of Pounds 9.1m.
Losses per share were 58.2p (11.3p earnings).
</TEXT>
