<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / UK Company News: MMC to investigate Alcatel's bid for STC
submarine division
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK Monopolies and Mergers Commission is to investigate the Pounds 600m
bid by Alcatel, the French telecommunications equipment supplier, for STC
Submarine Systems, the UK-based submarine cable subsidiary of Northern
Telecom, of Canada.
Mr Michael Heseltine, secretary of state for trade and industry, has
referred the deal to the MMC following a recommendation by Sir Bryan
Carsberg, director-general of fair trading.
Analysts were surprised by the reference, given the international nature of
the undersea cable business and Northern Telecom's determination to sell
STC. More than 90 per cent of STC's cable systems are exported.
The European Commission's competition directorate cleared the takeover last
month.
Under the Fair Trading Act, the UK government has the power to refer mergers
to the MMC if they create or intensify a market share of more than 25 per
cent or if they involve assets worth more than Pounds 30m.
STC is a principal supplier of long-distance undersea fibre-optic systems to
British Telecommunications. BT made no formal objection to the Department of
Trade of Industry, although it is known to have had serious reservations
about the takeover.
The submarine cable division was acquired by Northern Telecom as part of its
Pounds 1.9bn takeover of STC in 1990.
Although profitable, Northern has been looking to sell it for some time. The
company has no submarine business in North America, and it sits uneasily
with its core businesses of transmission, switching, radio/microwave and
integrated networks.
If the Alcatel deal is not agreed, the future of STC looks highly uncertain.
It currently has 1,200 employees, mostly in Greenwich, London.
Alcatel said yesterday it was 'not surprised' by the reference, given its
size.
'We nonetheless regret the delay caused, because we want to create a strong
European undersea cable business.'
STC estimated that since 1985 it had won about 23 per cent of the Pounds
6.8bn long-distance submarine cable market.
AT&amp;T, the US giant, was the market leader with about 37 per cent; Alcatel
had gained about 19 per cent; and NEC and Fujitsu of Japan had about 18 per
cent between them.
BT is concerned about the reduction of competition in the undersea cable
market, and the possibility that it could become reliant on AT&amp;T.
Lex, Page 24
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Alcatel Alsthom.
    STC Submarine Systems.
    Northern Telecom.
</CO>
