<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / UK Company News: Charles Sidney's 110p share price values
company at Pounds 26m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Charles Sidney, the Yorkshire-based Mercedes-Benz commercial
vehicle and passenger car dealer which is coming to market through a full
placing and public offer, were priced at 110p each yesterday valuing the
group at Pounds 26m.
Albert Fisher, the food processing and distribution group, is divesting
Charles Sidney as part of a strategy to refocus the group on its core
activities.
Albert Fisher is selling 20m shares as part of the placing and public offer
and will use the proceeds to reduce debt. The offer will also raise about
Pounds 3.6m, net of expenses, for Charles Sidney which plans to use the
funds to take advantage of acquisition opportunities.
Charles Sidney reported pre-tax profits of Pounds 2.46m (Pounds 1.7m) in the
year to August 31 on turnover of Pounds 55.7m (Pounds 41.3m). Earnings per
share increased to 7.9p (5.6p) and the notional dividend is 3.5p.
Although the group has not produced any profits forecasts for the current
year, the prospectus says that the directors believe Charles Sidney is 'well
placed to benefit from the recent increase in Mercedes-Benz's market share
in the commercial vehicle sector,' and that they expect a 'significant
improvement' in Mercedes-Benz car sales following the recent launch of its
new range of cars.
The placing and public offer is sponsored by Schroders and dealings in the
new shares are expected to begin on November 10.
COMMENT
Charles Sidney is coming to market at an opportune time. The recovery in the
luxury car sector appears to have arrived along with Mercedes-Benz's new
models. Meanwhile the group's long-term profitability is underpinned by its
solid commercial vehicle operations. At the offer price the stock would be
trading on a historic multiple of 14 - a reasonable discount to some of its
more established quoted counterparts.
</TEXT>
