<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / DFS prospectus reveals cash moves
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PATHFINDER prospectus for DFS Furniture, issued yesterday, reveals the
extent to which Mr Graham Kirkham, executive chairman and, with his family,
100 per cent shareholder, has taken cash out of the specialist upholstery
retailer in recent years.
In the year to August 1 1993 there were non-recurring directors' emoluments
of Pounds 9.54m and pension contributions of Pounds 3.84m. Substantial
payments have been paid in each year since 1989-90.
Until this month, when Mr Christopher Ferris joined as finance director, the
group only had two executive directors, Mr Kirkham and Mr Jon Massey, chief
operating officer.
The company also paid or proposed dividends of Pounds 7m in respect of the
1992-93 year. Mr Kirkham took Pounds 5.53m of his emoluments in 'works of
art and antiques'.
As a result of the non-recurring emoluments and the dividends, there was a
retained loss for the year of Pounds 2.23m.
In future Mr Kirkham will be paid Pounds 200,000 a year plus pension
contributions, a company car and medical insurance.
The prospectus also reveals that Mr Tony Ashwell, aged 45, one of 16 senior
managers in the tier immediately below board level, has been charged with
driving whilst disqualified, refusing to provide a breathalyser test and 'a
number of other offences' following 'an incident' in August this year.
Mr Kirkham and his family will sell about half the company's shares in the
flotation which is expected to value the company at about Pounds 200m.
The prospectus shows that profits before non-recurring items and tax rose to
Pounds 20.8m in the year to August 1 from Pounds 14.9m. This includes
interest receivable of Pounds 1.29m and a profit of Pounds 870,000 on asset
sales. Sales rose by 38 per cent to Pounds 114.2m. Since 1989 sales have
grown at 35 per cent a year compound and operating profits by 46 per cent
compound. Operating margins have exceeded 15 per cent each year since 1990.
The group has no debt and its cash reserves will be Pounds 13m after the
float.
Mr Kirkham said the group had 'a proven formula that travels well' and 'an
excessive obsession with the bottom line'. Its 27 stores reach about a third
of the population of mainland UK, and the group aims to achieve nationwide
coverage. That could mean 70 to 80 stores eventually.
</TEXT>
