<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Globex faces reshaping
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GLOBEX, the electronic futures trading system developed by Reuters and the
world's two largest futures exchanges, is likely to be radically
restructured, when the agreement between its backers is renegotiated in
April.
Yesterday, the chairmen of both the Chicago Board of Trade and the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange - two of the three backers of the Dollars 80m (Pounds
54m) system - jockeyed for position, as one announced that he would be
willing to give up some control of the system, while the other arrived in
London for private talks with Reuters.
Launched 18 months ago, Globex has been dogged by low trading volume, delays
in gaining regulatory approval to install screens, unwillingness of other
exchanges to sign up, and bickering between the two exchanges.
Looking ahead to the April negotiations, Mr Pat Arbor, CBOT chairman, said
his exchange was prepared to give up control of the day-to-day running of
the system to attract other exchanges. Globex 'will look more democratic,
more open, more like a utility.'
Currently, Reuters operates the system, but the two exchanges control
trading on it. Other exchanges, including the London International Financial
Futures &amp; Options Exchange, have said they were unwilling to surrender
control of their products to competitors by joining.
Reuters will have the option to pull out of Globex in April, because the
CBOT and CME will not have met trading targets of 50,000 contracts a day
between them on the system. Currently, they are trading around 5,000
contracts a day. Globex needs to attract new exchanges in order to boost
volume and allow Reuters to recoup its estimated Dollars 75m investment.
Only France's Matif has joined so far.
Reuters declined to comment yesterday, but, in a recent interview with the
Financial Times, Ms Rosalyn Wilton, managing director of Reuters transaction
products, said: 'We want to explore all the various avenues and
opportunities. We want to be able to do something that is right for the
marketplace.' She added: 'One could ask what is the way to make it easier
(for other exchanges) and to inspire more confidence.'
It emerged yesterday that Mr Jack Sandner, the CME chairman, has come to
London for private discussions with Mr Peter Job, chief executive of
Reuters. Mr Sandner said he would talk about the CME's 'long-term
relationship with Reuters'.
</TEXT>
