<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / A pile of money in search of a home: The public clamour for
a stake in the Singapore Telecom privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Public disturbances are rare in tightly controlled Singapore. But share
frenzy has been sweeping across the island republic. The centre of attention
has been the partial privatisation of Singapore Telecom (ST). The government
valuation of SDollars 30.5bn will make it Singapore's biggest quoted
company, accounting for 20 per cent of total stock market capitalisation.
'For a company with a domestic market of less than 3m people and only
limited investments overseas, a valuation of that order is a considerable
achievement,' says one telecommunications analyst. 'But it's really more a
reflection of the enormous amount of funds available for share buying within
Singapore - backed up by the weight of equity investment funds washing in
from overseas.'
Earlier this year the government announced a relaxation of strict rules
governing the use of funds held by Singaporeans in the central provident
fund (CPF), a compulsory savings scheme. More than SDollars 20bn of
additional CPF funds were made available to buy shares.
Group A ST shares, sold at Dollars 1.90, are available to Singaporeans to
buy through their CPF accounts. The initial limit of 600 shares each is
being increased by the government. Group B shares are available to
Singporeans at SDollars 2 each, with a limit of 1,000 shares per applicant.
Group C shares are causing the most excitement. These are available by way
of a single strike price tender at or above SDollars 2 each. Such has been
the interest, there are fears that a 'freak' high price could be set. 'You'd
be mad to bid above SDollars 3.50 a share,' says one foreign broker. 'But
the way this sale has been hyped, and given the amount of money around,
anything could happen.'
While foreign fund managers involved in Asian markets are anxious to include
ST in their investment portfolios, many are being cautious about the
tendering process and prefer to wait for a secondary market to develop. Some
foreign buyers object to paying more than Singaporeans, while others point
out that even the basic launch price sets an unduly high prospective
price-earnings ratio of 27.
But indications are that it is Singaporeans themselves who are leading the
rush to put in tenders for the Group C shares.
Singapore is sitting on a mountain of savings. It has foreign exchange
reserves of more than USDollars 40bn. CPF assets are now put at SDollars
50bn. More than 90 per cent of the population own their homes, and the roads
are full of expensive cars. Share buying is one of the few avenues left for
Singporeans to use up excess funds. There are dangers lurking amid all the
market euphoria. The government deliberately structured the ST sale to
encourage long-term share ownership. Yet the likely success of the issue, in
part due to a government sponsored publicity campaign extolling the benefits
of share ownership, could defeat the government's objectives.
Analysts say that if the Group C strike price is much above the SDollars
2.50 mark, group B shareholders will probably quickly offload their shares.
If the price goes above SDollars 3 then some group A shareholders might also
be tempted to forego their future discounts and sell.
Earlier this week, Mr Goh Chok Tong, the prime minister, said there was no
doubt that some Singaporeans would get get their fingers burnt. 'The balloon
will have to burst some time.'
</TEXT>
