<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Revolt over defence cuts could threaten government majority
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ROW in Tory ranks over further defence cuts erupted with renewed vigour
yesterday on the eve of the first full cabinet discussion of departmental
spending targets for the next three years.
A group of 14 Tory MPs signed a letter threatening to vote against any move
to impose more 'substantial' defence cuts. Any such cuts would 'seriously
jeopardise the capability of this country's military forces to defend it',
the letter warned.
A rebellion on this scale would overturn the government's precarious
17-strong majority. Its possibility will strengthen the hand of Mr Malcolm
Rifkind, the defence secretary, ahead of what is certain to be a lively
cabinet meeting. After two months of discussions with ministers, the
so-called EDX spending committee has now finalised its recommendations for
departmental budgets until 1996-97. But it has not achieved a firm
settlement, leaving the final deal to be hammered out in cabinet.
Downing Street acknowledged yesterday that more than one cabinet meeting
might be needed to secure an agreement.
Yesterday's letter - delivered personally to the prime minister, Mr John
Major, by Sir Nicholas Bonsor, Tory chairman of the Commons defence
committee - follows reports that the Treasury was targeting the Ministry of
Defence for up to Pounds 1bn of new cuts.
Although a partial retreat by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, is thought
to have defused Mr Rifkind's threat to demand a full defence review, the
defence secretary is expected to use today's meeting to oppose those cuts
still demanded.
The letter, which the signatories did not intend to be made public, argued
that Britain's defence forces were 'at best already fully stretched'.
Signatories included Sir Jerry Wiggin, the former defence minister, Mr
Patrick Cormack (Staffordshire South), Mr Christopher Gill, the Eurosceptic
MP for Ludlow, and Mr Cyril Townsend (Bexleyheath). It later emerged that
the number of signatures might understate the scale of the threatened
rebellion, as some Tories complained they were not asked to sign it.
Political notebook, Page 8
</TEXT>
