<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / The Lex Column: New issues
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
UK corporate financiers may have few takeovers to handle, but they have
rarely been busier. There has been a record Pounds 9.6bn worth of rights
issues in the first nine months of 1993. That flow of rights is now ebbing -
at least partly because almost any company with a plausible tale to tell has
already told it at least once. But flotations are filling the gap. Some
Pounds 2.7bn has been raised so far this year - including Pounds 140m by
four companies yesterday. Management buy-outs and investment trusts figure
strongly among fund-raisers. MBOs which have done well are presumably being
pressed by their backers to provide an exit route. Those which have done
badly are doubtless encouraged to repay debt before their cash flow
implodes. And new investment trusts are a consequence of narrowing discounts
and the flood of retail funds into collective investments.
Some companies are also raising funds for expansion and several quoted
groups are selling off divisions to the market. Both routes imply a
reluctance to take on further debt for expansion. They also suggest that
companies think the equity market is overpaying. Indeed, stock market
valuations are currently almost twice those of trade sales which managers
price themselves. That chimes with the caution of those company directors at
recent interim results who found the level of equities difficult to
comprehend. It may mean nothing - managers were, after all, poor judges of
the onset of recession. But it will be interesting to see whether fund
managers continue to take assets from companies at current prices.
</TEXT>
