<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / The Lex Column: Alcatel/Northern
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine's referral to the MMC of Alcatel's proposed acquisition
of Northern Telecom's undersea cables business raises some ticklish issues
of international competition policy. The EC has sidestepped consideration of
the deal because it did not reach its turnover threshold. Yet it is not
immediately clear why UK competition authorities should become so agitated,
given that national market shares are somewhat meaningless in the undersea
cables business. After expressing some earlier reservations, even BT
refrained from making representations to the OFT.
From a global perspective, however, there is perhaps cause for
consternation. The international market is consolidating fast, raising fears
of cartelisation. Alcatel suggests that of all the undersea fibre-optic
cable installed since 1985, AT&amp;T accounts for 37 per cent of the Dollars
10bn market, Northern 23 per cent, Alcatel 19 per cent, and a Japanese
consortium 18 per cent. Even considering Mr Heseltine's fondness for
European industrial champions, consummation of the proposed merger would
represent a worrying degree of concentration.
In the past, national competition authorities have acted together to block
contentious international acquisitions - Gillette's proposed deal with
Eemland being the most notable example. But this is an unsatisfactory and
haphazard procedure. Nascent proposals to include international competition
issues in the next round of Gatt talks should be developed.
</TEXT>
