<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Observer: Empire line
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
While Russia's politicians haggle over the future of Lenin's embalmed body,
Leonid Brezhnev's luxury ambulance has drawn up inside Russia's Imperial
Bank.
Having paid Dollars 250,000 for the artefact in a charity auction jointly
organised by Sotheby's, the bank plans to show off its acquisition across
Europe. For the Zil is part of a sculpture known as the 'sleeping beauty'
which also features a young woman lying on a tomb  - a combination which,
according to Russian art experts, symbolises potential democratic power.
'This is the new imperial style in art. It suits us because we have become a
financial empire,' explains the bank which has recently entered into an
alliance with two other Russian finance houses. Indeed, it is evidently
quite taken with the regal theme. A recent advertising campaign depicts the
emperor Caesar under the slogan: 'Punctuality is the courtesy of Kings.'
