</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Personal View: The multiple benefits of a single tier
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID CURRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Take the annual sales of Sainsbury's superstores. Add those of Tesco,
Safeway and Asda. It adds up to Pounds 25bn but it is barely a third of the
amount spent every year by local government. This year local councils will
spend Pounds 70bn; their spending on services alone will total Pounds 43bn.
Town halls are in the front line of service delivery. Local government is in
more frequent contact with most citizens and most businesses than the
legendary Sir Humphreys of Whitehall departments.
Concern about the cost effectiveness of that spending and the efficiency of
service delivery led the government to question whether the traditional
two-tier structure of local government in shire England was still the best
model. As a result a year ago we set up the Local Government Commission
under Sir John Banham to make recommendations on the future shape of local
government.
But because it was accepted that the review's programme was too long (the
final tranche of counties would still be in the melting pot in 1997) and
that the government's own preference was not explicit, the government has
since changed the Commission's guidelines. This should now mean that the
Commission's work will be finished by the end of next year. Many new local
authorities will come into being in 1996, and the rest the year after.
The government has also come down more emphatically in favour of all-purpose
unitary councils to replace the two-tier system, without ruling out some
two-tier structures.
Why has the Government decided to press-ahead with reform? The pitfalls of
trying to satisfy the views of local councillors (who form the hard core of
party activists in all political parties), MPs, local government employees
(2m of them) and getting all this through Parliament are all too obvious.
The situation has not been made easier by the passionate frontier wars waged
locally by councils armed with specially commissioned consultants reports
asserting their claim to primacy or survival.
But there are three good reasons for pushing ahead with reform:
To rationalise the delivery of services. It makes no sense for social
services and housing to be divided between county and district authorities
respectively. Nor is it obvious, for example, that county control of
highways planning and district control of planning for business or
residential development makes for easy decision taking. The current system
is confusing. There is no single door to knock on for service delivery or
redress. The number of councillors who serve on both county and district is
perhaps an indicator of the present unsatisfactory divide: accountability
must be better served by all-purpose councils.
The role of councils has changed fundamentally in recent years. Increasingly
councils are the commissioners and procurers, rather than providers, of
services. Compulsory competitive tendering is already established in
blue-collar services such as refuse collection and is to be introduced in
professional services such as architecture and legal work.
The case for a single tier of such 'enabling' councils is strong. They will
be powerful customers for business. Local government functions have become
more managerial and supervisory and the range of functions itself has
changed. The government has turned either to more executive methods - for
instance, using urban development councils to fulfil tasks such as inner
city regeneration - or to direct empowerment of local people, as in
education where budget decisions have been devolved to the head teacher's
study.
This has been a revolution, but a revolution largely between central and
local government itself with little debate outside the circle of those
directly involved. The reform of local government structure is a logical
response to this revolution. Of course it will pose problems of its own -
how to achieve a unitary authority large enough to tackle strategic issues
(planning, waste disposal, transport) without surrendering local identity
and accountability (the answer may be in devolving some service delivery to
existing town and parish councils). But at the end of the day it should
deliver streamlined local government which provides a one-stop shop for
citizens, and councils with which business can do business.
The author is local government minister for England
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
