<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Leading Article: Atom smash
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN physicists are lamenting the messy death of the Dollars 11bn
Superconducting Super Collider. Congress killed the project last week after
spending Dollars 2bn digging 15 miles of tunnel under the Texan plains for
what would have been the world's most powerful atom smasher. SSC enthusiasts
claim its demise could set back by a generation the search for an
all-encompassing theory of matter.
The view from the other side of the Atlantic is different. European
scientists - while not exactly wishing the SSC dead - point out that a
Pounds 1bn machine planned by Cern, the 18-nation particle physics research
centre near Geneva, could answer many of the same fundamental questions far
more cheaply.
From outside the world of particle physics, the demise of the mother of all
big science projects looks like a golden opportunity to enter a new era of
global co-operation. For too long the US has insisted on having national
facilities in every field of research, even when these represented costly
duplication of efforts elsewhere. The Americans have sometimes made gauche
gestures of international collaboration - like the belated approach to Japan
for help with the SSC - while insisting on keeping control of the project
firmly in their own hands.
A delicate gesture must now come from Europe. The 18 science ministers who
are due to meet in December for a presentation of Cern's proposed new atom
smasher, the Large Hadron Collider, should announce their intention to
convert Cern to a global centre for particle physics research. At the same
time they should invite the US and Japan to join as associate members.
Tact will be essential to heal the wounded pride of American physicists and,
most importantly, to convince Congress that a small portion of the money
saved by axing SSC should be spent in Geneva. European governments must not
give the impression that they are simply after US cash, so they can cut
their own contributions to Cern.
Fortunately, the congressional language terminating the SSC told the US
energy department to examine 'the feasibility of using SSC assets in whole
or in part in pursuit of an international high energy physics endeavour'.
The most persuasive argument is that US participation in Cern will give
fruitful employment to some of the 1,000 physicists who have been devoting
their talents to the SSC. It is not too late for the US to make a real
contribution to the new European collider; one of the two giant particle
detectors planned for Texas could be installed in Geneva instead.
Ironically, Cern is in practice already a global facility. One hundred
Japanese and 500 Americans already use its facilities as visiting scientists
supported by their own universities. The time has now come to bring their
governments - and others such as Canada and Korea - formally into the Cern
fold.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    XGZ  Europe.
</CN>
