<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Letters to the Editor: A night of hype at the opera
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr GRAHAM MELMOTH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I was struck by David Murray's determinedly favourable review of the
Wexford Festival production of the opera Zampa (October 19), echoing the
conventional wisdom around the town. It was hyped up for me by the
production team located in the row immediately behind where I sat in the
Theatre Royal, laughing, clapping and stamping at the sheer ingenuity and
vitality of it all. Indeed, it was quite a relief at the end that they left
to bask in the curtain calls they had helped to generate. I rather shared
the opinion of the lady accompanying a senior UK operator, overheard during
the interval, who said the production was a cross between Gilbert and
Sullivan and Hello, Hello.
I fear the contrasting reticence of the note-taking producer of the Barber
of Seville and her team sitting mutely in front of us the previous evening
will result in an equally undeserved review - the cognoscenti in that case
appearing to give it the thumbs down, without appreciating the quality and
originality of the production.
The producer, designers and general hangers-on should stay back stage during
performances, failing which they should not indulge in what might, in other
circumstances, be described as talking up the share price.
Graham Melmoth,
Throttles Nest,
Whitney Croft,
Higher Fence Road,
Maccelsfield SK10 1RQ
