<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Economic Viewpoint: Case for EC-wide cuts in tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SAMUEL BRITTAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Let us consider a dynamic economy, such as Japan 20-30 years ago, or some of
the east Asian 'tigers' today, whose trend growth rate is not far from 10
per cent a year. For such countries a growth rate of 5 per cent represents
recession and one of zero a slump.
Although different numbers apply to the more sluggish European economies,
the principles are the same. If the trend growth rate is about 3 per cent a
year, then an achieved rate of, say, 1 1/2 per cent represents continued
deterioration. The British Treasury made a great song and dance about the
continued gradual rise in real gross domestic product shown by the Central
Statistical Office's newly devised preliminary snapshot for the third
quarter - an indicator which, with a heavy dose of political interpretation,
took up most of last Friday's front page in the Evening Standard.
Let us, however, assume that this estimate is not revised substantially in
either direction. What it shows is that non-oil real GDP has been growing by
about 1.8 per cent a year since the end of 1992.
(The Treasury is entitled to exclude the highly volatile oil component to
measure the underlying movement. But it must be held to this convention,
even when it would suit it to take GDP including oil.)
The main point, however, is that an annual growth rate of 1.8 per cent is
well below most estimates of the trend growth of UK productive capacity.
What has been happening can be described as an incomplete recovery, a weak
recovery or even a worsening depression. The best term is the American
'growth recession'. What this means is that output is rising modestly, but
employment is still falling and the degree of slack increasing.
The same errors are being committed at a European level. The European
Commission is forecasting a Community recovery with output rising by 1 per
cent to 2 per cent in 1994. A similar prospect is held in store by a
majority of the German economic forecasting institutes, with one strong
dissentient. But even if the mainstream view is right, European unemployment
will continue to increase, together with unused capacity; and the atmosphere
of gloom, doom and protectionism will increase until growth recovers to the
3 per cent or so break-even point required before slack can be absorbed.
Much of the fashionable talk about growth in itself not bringing more jobs
simply reflects the fact that growth is insufficient, even bearing in mind
the need to prevent inflation from breaking out again.
Meanwhile, I could, if anyone were listening, help defuse a disagreement
between Mr Kenneth Clarke, the British chancellor, and Mr Jaques Delors, the
EC president. The latter would like more public infrastructure spending to
create jobs. Mr Clarke replies that it is not governments' task to spend to
create demand.
But it is their task, chancellor, it is - interpreting 'governments' broadly
to include central banks as well as finance ministers. Demand management has
been discredited because it was conducted in the past without regard to
inflation. But that is no excuse for throwing out the baby with the bath
water. Policies to raise demand need not involve increased government
spending or increasing the state's role in the economy.
The basic Keynesian equations show that an increase in private spending is
just as good as an increase in the government variety in promoting output
and employment - Keynes's own prejudices about infrastructure
notwithstanding. The one, narrow-minded and disgracefully protectionist
argument for preferring the government variety is that a higher proportion
of private spending 'leaks' into imports. But the whole virtue of a
European-wide approach is that these leakages cancel each other out.
What this is leading up to is that a European-wide tax cut would be as good
from the demand stimulation point of view as Mr Delors' infrastructure
spending; and it would be better from the point of view of supply-side
incentives and the signals it would send out.
Life, of course, is never that simple; and with so many countries suffering
from structural deficits, a low-tax strategy could in some places - although
I hope not everywhere - mean cancelling tax increases which might otherwise
have been made. Ronald Reagan was right to suspect that higher taxes end up
as higher government spending.
Equity delusions
The stock market has a reputation for forecasting 'five out of the last
three recessions'. In other words it is worth taking into account, but it
has a medium-term volatility which makes it an unreliable indicator on its
own. The chart shows that the FT-A 500 Index suggested a 1988 slump instead
of an inflationary boom, and - along with the Treasury and most mainstream
forecasters - indicated a premature 'green shoots' recovery from the 1990
recession.
Misleading, only to a lesser degree, has been the CBI optimism indicator,
even allowing for the fact that, as Mr Doug McWilliams of the Centre for
Economics and Business Research explains, about a half of the 30 percentage
point deterioration in the past six months is seasonal. (Why cannot the CBI
publish its data in seasonally adjusted form?)
The least unreliable CBI indicator has been that of recorded (not expected)
output and orders. True, this is not forward-looking. But it is a gain to
have some clue to the present, which official statistics, because of
irreducable lags, cannot provide. Another moral from the charts is that in
spite of the notorious damage inflicted on services by the recent recession,
manufacturing is still far more volatile than GDP as a whole.
Meanwhile, a Cambridge academic, Cliff Pratten, has made a systematic study
of the equity markets over many decades*. He discusses both the efficient
market hypothesis (EMH) and Keynes's view of a fragile conventional
valuation in which professional investors are trying to guess what other
investors are going to think. The moral of both views is the futility of
hoping to outwit the market by studying long-term prospects for profits: in
Keynes's view because it is futile and on the EMH because the information,
such as it is, is 'already in the market'.
Mr Pratten does say that some institutions have done better than the market
for quite long periods, but he does not give us their names or assure us
that they will continue to do so.
While financial commentators tend to worry that equities are vulnerable
after a rise such as the most recent one, academics like Mr Pratten find
evidence that equities are under-valued in relation to the most plausible
future movements of dividends, prices and interest rates.
Since Mr Pratten went to press two years ago, equity markets have risen by
nearly 20 per cent, of which about 12 per cent represents real appreciation
 -hardly enough to dent his view.
One reason why academics are more inclined to find under-valuation is that
they see the boom of the 1980s in a longer perspective, and that boom still
only took real share prices up to the level of the late 1930s. Meanwhile, I
know that current equity prices, like market exchange rates, give a bad
guide to future performance; but I also know that there is no one on whom I
could rely to give a better estimate of the centre of the likely probability
range.
*The Stock Market, Cambridge, Pounds 27.95.
</TEXT>
<XX>
