<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Letters to the Editor: Room for geo-centric Germany
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr COURTNEY D SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Mr Waigel, Germany's Finance Minister, makes some valid points in his
Personal View (October 12). But he tries to show Germany is not responsible
for high interest rates and slow economic growth by ignoring the linkages
between the German economy and the rest of Europe.
Economic pressures in one country are transmitted to other countries if
their exchange rates are fixed. The exchange rate mechanism eliminated the
one way countries could keep their economic policies separate: an adjustment
in the exchange rate.
If one economically powerful nation, such as Germany, raises interest rates
for very domestic considerations, the effect will be felt in other
countries, since the exchange rate cannot be changed.
Widening the ERM bands to 15 per cent will allow Germany to pursue a more
geo-centric policy with much less effect on other countries.
Courtney D Smith,
president,
Quantum Financial Services, 209 South Lasalle Street,
Chicago, Il, 60604.
</TEXT>
