<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Book Review: Out of the cold war into a cool calm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW GOWERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE COLD WAR AND THE MAKING OF THE MODERN WORLD
By Martin Walker
Fourth Estate Pounds 18.99, 404pp
It's over, and so am I,' says spymaster George Smiley at the end of John Le
Carre's last cold war novel, The Secret Pilgrim. 'Absolutely over. Time you
rang down the curtain on yesterday's cold warrior.' And in a weary
valediction, he preaches of the shifts in economic power that had brought
the conflict between east and west to an end; the need now for partnership
with Russia and, above all, for adjustment in the west. 'It's not only our
minds we're going to have to reconstruct,' he concludes. 'It's the
over-mighty modern state we've built for ourselves as a bastion against
something that isn't there any more.'
There is a similar valedictory feel to Martin Walker's new history of the
cold war. For more than four decades, confrontation between America and its
allies on the one hand and the Soviet empire and its proxies on the other
was the central fact around which the world organised its life -
politically, militarily, economically, socially. Now its removal has left
the countries of what used to be called 'the free world' - as much as those
liberated from communism - floundering, exhausted, groping for a sense of
collective purpose.
It may seem rather an obvious point, but it is still worth making. Four
years after the Berlin Wall came down, the cold war seems both too recent to
place in perspective and too remote to treat as anything other than a
distant memory.
With this book, Walker - Washington bureau chief of the Guardian, former
Moscow correspondent and child of the cold war generation - bravely steps
into the breach. Relying on extensive reading (though not, disappointingly,
on much original research), he escorts the reader from Yalta and the US
policy of 'containing' the Soviet threat, through the balance of terror
between US and Soviet nuclear arsenals, the proxy wars in the third world
and detente in Europe, to the crumbling of communism and 'victory' of the
west in the late 1980s.
The cold war was more of a global conflict than either of this century's two
world wars, and more than a confrontation between states or even empires: in
Walker's words it was a 'total war between economic and social systems, an
industrial test to destruction'.
By adopting this broad approach, he reminds us of a fact it is easy to
forget after such a seismic change in the world's affairs: there were many
occasions from the late 1940s when victory seemed far from assured, and that
lent the efforts of post-war western leaders a peculiar urgency. Whether in
rebuilding western Europe and Japan after the war, in competing with the
apparent success of the Soviet economy in the 1950s, in combating the spread
of Soviet influence in the developing world in the 1960s or simply in
meeting the military threat of an unpredictable nuclear superpower, every
government in the west was united by the same compulsion.
But there was another factor that lent the years of confrontation a
comforting sense of predictability. By the 1960s, the cold war had become
something of an institution with its own warped logic, codes of etiquette -
and, in a curious way, stability.
Walker writes well of the 'subtle gamesmanship' that developed between
Washington and Moscow as a result of the nuclear standoff - their sporadic
skirmishing through third parties in every arena of the world except the
most central one of Europe; the 'curious empathy' that evolved between them,
turning a shared need to avoid mutual destruction into a protracted pas de
deux over arms control.
Ultimately though, the cold war was fought and won on the economic
battlefield more than the political or military ones. Walker does not
underestimate the role played in ending the confrontation by remarkable men
such as Mikhail Gorbachev and, he has sneakingly to admit, Ronald Reagan.
Nor does he ignore the influence of the breezes in Europe, east and west,
that brought about greater communication and political transparency across
the Iron Curtain.
But in the last analysis, he argues, it was the weaknesses of the Soviet
economy - masked for a time by rising oil revenues in the Brezhnev years,
exposed when Moscow struggled to meet Washington's deficit spending splurge
in the 1980s - that brought the Soviet empire to its knees. Equally, from
the Marshall Plan in western Europe and the Korean war boom in Asia, it was
the superior ability of market economies - and social democratic variants
thereon - to provide guns for the state and butter for its citizens that
kept communism at bay. The irony is that this very effort - especially
during the sinew-straining 1980s - has left the west, as well as the east,
facing the need for economic and political adjustment.
At times Walker, whose writing is fluent but frequently glib, takes the
east-west analogies irritatingly far. Is it really fair to say, for example,
that America's difficulties over Vietnam in the late 1960s meant that 'the
two main political systems had rarely looked more alike, or less savoury'?
Or that: 'In the aftermath of the cold war, in the final months of the Bush
presidency, the US seemed to be stumbling painfully through its own Brezhnev
era'?
His conclusions, however, are undoubtedly right: that the west is now
struggling to adapt to an age when the global economic forces unleashed in
the battle against communism are challenging the traditional nation state.
With economic power now more evenly spread between the US, western Europe
and Japan - and with the Chinese juggernaut, too, advancing rapidly towards
the market - the next challenge is to maintain and extend that process of
integration, whether by working harder to bring Russia into the fold of
market economies or, more generally, by preventing the trade barriers from
going up again.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
