<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Letters to the Editor: Technical fixes don't make good
policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Prof CHRISTOPHER BLISS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, In his article of October 26 ('Time to retune for Emu harmony'), Sir
Leon Brittan claims that everything can be on course for Emu if inflation
rate co-ordination is substituted for over-rigid interest rate and exchange
rate co-ordination. So much for a past in which, for many European
governments, maintaining the exchange rate within a narrow band was taken to
be the vehicle of inflation rate convergence.
The realities of the European situation are not so simple that Sir Leon's
new formula will work any better than the old. Even if inflation convergence
could be achieved by monetary targeting, that could leave individual
countries with widely divergent unemployment rates. Then exchange rates
would be correct only in a transitory and insecure sense. To lock them at
that point with an Emu key, as Sir Leon would wish, would be to throw all
subsequent burdens of adjustment on to national flexibility and migration.
The problem at its root is that EC Europe is not an optimal currency area
and cannot easily become one. To slide around that obstacle with fine words,
new targets, and technical fixes, will neither establish good economic
policy, nor will it work as politics. Germany, in particular, is unlikely to
settle for an insubstantial convergence defined by formulae convenient at
the time.
Christopher Bliss,
Nuffield professor of
international economics,
Nuffield College,
Oxford OX1 1NF
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
