<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Arts: Variations on an enigma - Theatre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MALCOLM RUTHERFORD and ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The first act of Elgar's Rondo has such a stirring end that a great deal
else can be forgiven. In comes the band of the Worcestershire Regiment
playing Land of Hope and Glory with all the pomp and circumstance that can
be fitted into the RSC's Swan Theatre.
The band plays again in the second act in the presence of King George V, who
goes to sleep. There is other music, notably the movement from Elgar's
Second Symphony, which gives its title to the piece.
David Pownall has written a middlingly good middlebrow play which leaves a
lot of loose ends. Experts on Elgar may be just as confused as those who
know little about him.
There is general consent that he was the first English composer of
international standing since Henry Purcell two centuries before. He took his
inspiration from the Germans. He was very much a man of the Midlands, which
is an excellent reason for this play being premiered in Stratford. After his
wife died in 1920 he wrote little more original music, although he lived
until 1934.
As a young man he was the bandmaster at the Worcestershire County lunatic
asylum, his father having been unable to afford to send him to the Leipzig
Conservatory. He was admired by George Bernard Shaw, and was the first major
composer to realise the possibilities of the gramophone.
Pownall picks up some of the facts and tries to develop a thesis of his own.
This is that Elgar was hurt by his lighter pieces going down well in England
while his more ambitious work was admired mainly on the Continent. At the
same time, the early years of the 20th century were not a good period for an
English composer who loved Germany. Elgar began to dry up and the Third
Symphony was never completed.
It is quite fun in parts. Alec McCowen is a wonderful broody Elgar and there
is an outstanding performance by Ian Hughes as a young Catholic priest. But
it does not fit together. Characters such as George V and GBS wander in and
out. Elgar's wife Alice, played by Sheila Ballantine, is so repetitively
snobbish as not to be credible. Nothing about her is developed.
There are moments of knockabout music hall comedy - 'watch your back,
Dvorak, don't be so juicy, Debussy' - also a curiously embittered gardener
who pees in the cider. Some facts, such as Elgar's period as bandmaster in
the mental home, are unjustifiably taken for granted.
The direction is by Di Trevis. She could have had a more ordered text.
Still, there is always Land of Hope and Glory to look back on.
The Royal Shakespeare Company has bucked the trend of declining theatre
audiences and reported attendances of 90 per cent of capacity at Stratford
on Avon and the Barbican in 1992-93, writes Antony Thorncroft. This was a 2
per cent rise on the previous year. The RSC reduced its dependency on
subsidy per paid admission from Pounds 10.16 to Pounds 9.54.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7922 Theatrical Producers and Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 21
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT934-12089</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DJ1C4AC6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931028
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Arts: The touch of a virtuoso - Cinema
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL ANDREWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PIANO (15) Jane Campion
DIRTY WEEKEND (18) Michael Winner
HOCUS POCUS (PG) Kenny Ortega
IT IS the 1850s. You are a mute Scottish woman sent to wildest New Zealand
to marry a landowner you have never met. Your father arranged the marriage;
your little daughter goes with you. You insist on taking one luxury object,
your piano. You already hold the Bible and the complete works of Shakespeare
 -or much of them - inside your grave, well-schooled Victorian head.
But soon things will change. The brittle battlements of art and education
will be stormed by new emotions, new passions, new horrors.
Jane Campion's The Piano, which won this year's Cannes Golden Palm, is a
masterpiece: more, an astonishing masterpiece. We know we are on
inspiration's Cloud Nine from the early scenes. The black-garbed heroine
(Holly Hunter) transported ashore on sailors' shoulders looks like a giant
sea-born spider being carried towards Eden. Behind her the sky is a
lowering, ominous water-colour. Before her lies the beach, a silver-white
sheet on which she sets down her life's few, surreal essentials. Chiefly
that packing-cased piano, on which she plays a few wistful notes through a
crack in the planking.
But, first rumble of doom: husband-to-be Sam Neill will not spare the
servant-power to carry it to his home. Second rumble of doom: his estate
manager Baines (Harvey Keitel) will spare the manpower to carry it to his
home. With her piano held hostage by this Scottish hulk, half gone-native
with his daubs of Maori make-up, Hunter can only win the instrument back -
in key-by-key barter - by giving Keitel lessons.
The lessons consist of her offering him musical instruction and him offering
her initially-resisted physical attentions. These start with eyes poring
over her petite figure encased in voluminous black; then graduate to a
finger delicately sounding a stocking-hole; then consummate in an erotic
wrestling match watched by the horrified Neill. Once again a crack in wooden
planking is the fateful - soon to be tragic - point of access.
Is this the first ever film to depict the growth of erotic feelings from the
woman's viewpoint - first as victim, later as willing accomplice? Or is it
just the first film to do so unforgettably? Campion, with her cameraman
Stuart Dryburgh and sound designer Lee Smith, make the whole landscape of
this dank, twisted jungle seem part of the emotional maze closing around the
heroine. For days after seeing the movie, you hear the swish of hooped
dresses on muddy forest floor or the crackle of condescension, like dry
twigs, as Mr Neill's family 'welcomes' the new non-speaking bride. (Says an
aunt: 'There's nothing so easy to like as a pet and they're quite silent'.)
But this mute heroine presides over a movie of piercing eloquence. As well
as orchestrating her supersensitive soundtrack, Campion provides images that
swell in the memory. As in her first feature Sweetie - the calling-card of a
genius even before she gave us An Angel At My Table - the New Zealand-born
director's screen pictures are never just exotic backcloth. They extend
landscape and gesture, human face and inhuman wilderness into metaphor.
Marvel at the moment when the camera, placed behind Hunter, rises and moves
mysteriously in towards her hair-knot, then on beyond into the dark,
mist-strewn forest. It is as if we are passing right through her mind into
her mind's gathering nightmare.
The Piano is about disorientation. But more, it is about emotional
free-fall; about the fateful plunge we humans go on willingly risking - in
music, sex, passion, in almost every profound human transaction - from first
diffident address to ultimate self-offering or self-immolation.
If the love story is one variation on the theme, another is the heroine's
vertiginous reaching out towards another world, another culture. In this
imperial outpost barely quarantined from barbarism, superstition is not just
the natives' prerogative. The Victorian interlopers have their own dotty
mystical panaceas. When the adult-mimicking children are caught playing
games of mock sexual embrace with the forest trees, they are ordered by the
grown-ups to wash them down. In this empire of unreason Campion finds the
perfect setting for her climax of plausible horror. The discovery of
infidelity; the husband's rage; the act of mutilation; and the human cry so
loud, so unnerving that it seems to bounce off the heavens and back again.
But in this film, even after the horror, it is the mystery that we remember.
The words that never issue from Hunter's mouth - though we sense them moving
about behind those clenched, luminously responsive features - are the words
that never issue from the film. Born to deal with passions beyond reason, we
on Earth know that the inexpressible, the incommunicable, lives out there in
the jungle beyond words. The triumph of The Piano is that it finds a
language of its own in its vocabulary of image and metaphor; and that it
reminds us of a time, before the world was glibly dubbed a 'global village',
when human beings had a proper, primal awe of the distances separating land
from land, man from man, and man from woman.
Any movie week that starts with the sublime usually ends up with the other
commodity. Female self-emancipation comes in different sizes and guises, and
in Michael Winner's Dirty Weekend it is large, loud and lunatic. With
Charles Bronson now giving up mugger-chasing for free bus travel, Lia
Williams has been tapped as Mr W's new gun-toting, knife-toting,
scowl-toting citizen-vigilante.
She is Bella, heroine of Helen Zahavi's acclaimed (by some) novel about a
young woman who turns avenging angel against male harassment. She does this
over one busy weekend in Brighton. A hammer to the cranium of a Peeping Tom,
a plastic bag over the head of a Tired Businessman, bullets to the bodies of
three alley thugs . . . And the important thing is that Bella enjoys it all.
'This is jolly, isn't it?' she says during one paroxysm of perforation. And
by the final reel she is spending her last night in Brighton ridding the
famous pier of a vagrant serial killer.
Typically of a Winner film, this nocturnal finale takes place in what seems
to be broad daylight. But when did our Mr W ever care about realism? Enough
that the celluloid passes through the camera; that the post-dubbed voices
match the lip movements; and that a series of stalwart British actors earn
their crust by making unbelievable dialogue sound believable. Miss Williams,
fresh from Oleanna on the London stage, manages to give a demon polish even
to lines like 'You piece of stateless scum', uttered to Ian Richardson's
interesting impersonation of an Asian clairvoyant.
After a short struggle I gave up and enjoyed this film. Certainly it is
omega to the alpha of The Piano. Certainly it is crude, rude and
preposterous. But at least it is lively. And what is life without lurid
contrasts between the Good and Bad?
Anything would be better than Hocus Pocus. For dirty weekend read Disney
Hallowe'en. Bette Midler, wearing buck teeth and an orange fright-wig,
scampers across the skies of Salem, Massachusetts, casting spells, singing
songs and bearing an eerie resemblance to another famous lady with flashing
eyes and forceful front teeth. But 'Margaret Thatcher, The Salem Years'
this, alas, is not. Rather the film tells of three reincarnated witches and
the youngsters who tediously combat them, helped by a cat and a friendly
walking corpse. The script is bad, the songs worse, the jokes nowhere to be
found.
But then spoof Gothicism cannot be expected to flourish in the wake of
Vincent Price's death. That velvet snarl; that leonine scowl; farewell to
the greatest actor of his genre. I shall be writing more about the cinema's
Demon King, and recalling a recent conversation on Saturday.
</TEXT>
