<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Technology: Consultant's Critique - Software at Work
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN GRUMBALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Malcolm Newman, the driver behind the project, must be an amazing negotiator
 -many people have paid more for a feasibility study than he paid in
consultancy charges for his custom system. Unisys still retains the rights
to the software and is no doubt looking forward to more sales. This will
still benefit Sheffield City Council as it will receive royalties.
These sort of deals are becoming increasingly common as software houses
recognise the value of getting clients involved in design. Too often,
computer systems have been designed by programmers who have no idea of
business needs. They implement systems which are elegant in programming
terms but offer no value to an end-user. Persuading a real client to
co-operate in building the first version of a system is invaluable. It is
then relatively easy to implement the system in a way that allows it to be
re-used for other customers.
One of the paradoxes of computer systems is that things which are relatively
easy with manual systems can be difficult for computers.
Take the problem of matching a map's edges. Anyone who has used an atlas
knows the irritation when the road goes over a page boundary. But the eye
can make the join relatively easily. Not so with computer digitisation.
If a road goes off the edge of one map that has shrunk, on to one that has
stretched, there are many difficulties. Not only does the program have to
identify where the join should be, it has to adjust the lines on either side
of the join. For a computer system this involves complex mathematics.
Overall, I thought this was an exciting case study. The system will produce
real benefits for Sheffield residents. It uses some elegant software and
shows how the public and private sectors can work together for mutual
advantage.
I was impressed with Newman. He has a personal touch reminiscent of a
successful entrepreneur. He also drives a hard bargain - ask Unisys.
The author is a consultant at Software Design and Construction, of Milton
Keynes
</TEXT>
