<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Technology: Sheffield City Council - Software at Work
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANY SNAPSHOT
Nature of business: Sheffield City Council provides services to 501,000
people in an area of 36,000 hectares. It is run by 87 councillors (known as
members). The city hosts two universities, which increase the population
during term-time by 25,000. The care of 250 schools are included in its
educational duties, and its 76,000 council houses make it one of the biggest
property owners in the country.
Employees: 26,000.
Turnover: The council has a revenue budget of Pounds 700,000 per annum to
pay for the provision of services, and a capital budget of Pounds 50m to pay
for the improvements of housing stock, schools, etc, on an asset-base of
Pounds 10bn
Key personnel: Pamela Gordon, chief executive; Malcolm Newman, city
treasurer and deputy ceo; Wendy Miller, head of information technology; Alan
Platt, GIS project manager. Property services manager Jill Bungay is
programme director for the first two phases of the GIS.
TECHNOLOGY FILE
Software: Three bespoke geographical applications were developed by Unisys
for Sheffield, using the the ARGIS fourth-generation language: Terrier, the
land register, Highways (live September 93), and Cartography (live in May
93). Sheffield IT services has developed the Land Charges application
in-house. The database used to store references is Oracle.
Hardware: A pair of Unix-based Solborne 2000 servers, supporting seven PCs
and seven 17-inch Sun and Solborne workstations, connected on a fibre-optic
network.
Supplier: Unisys specified the hardware and provided consultancy and
development. Data capture included text and graphics, provisional quotes,
and specifications, and was subcontracted to Cork-based agency QC.
Other systems: Existing operational systems use a mixture of hardware,
largely ICL, including an SX 580-20 mainframe and 30 Unix-based minis.
Operational applications on housing, rents, etc, will be accessible via the
GIS.
Cost: Hardware is leased over a five-year period at Pounds 160,000.
Development and consultancy cost Pounds 140,000. Data capture, budgeted at
Pounds 300,000, now on a fixed price contract of Pounds 500,000. Estimated
savings - on map-handling and salaries over a five-year period - are
estimated at Pounds 335,000.
</TEXT>
