<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Warnings on credit adverts attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPULSORY 'health warnings' at the bottom of financial advertisements for
credit should be abolished or at least simplified, the Incorporated Society
of British Advertisers told an Office of Fair Trading inquiry yesterday.
Consumers are confused and put off by the pedantic wording of the warnings,
the advertisers' body told the inquiry into the working and enforcement of
the Consumer Credit Act 1974. The investigation forms part of the
government's drive to reduce unnecessary regulation.
The warnings on the possible consequences of defaulting on secured loans,
and information on, for example, how interest rates are calculated, must by
law appear at the end of all advertisements that involve credit
arrangements.
The rules cover advertisements for, among others, car loans, mortgages and
credit cards, and apply to radio and television as well as print
advertising.
Mr Kenneth Miles, director-general of the society, said there were 'no
grounds for regarding most financial advertising as deserving of suspicion'.
Consumers were in danger of suffering from 'information overload'.
The society is arguing for self-regulation and for the Advertising Standards
Authority, which is financed by an industry levy, to oversee credit
advertisements. The authority performed this function before 1980, when
regulations under the 1974 act came into effect.
The authority said yesterday that it would be prepared to take the job again
provided it had adequate resources. It said that complaints about consumer
credit could total 5,000 a year, on top of the 11,000 complaints about other
areas of advertising already handled.
The society's evidence was given on the first day of a two-day public
hearing in London.
</TEXT>
