<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Black cabs at risk in licensing review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE black taxi cab, a familiar symbol of London around the world, could
disappear as a result of a government review of taxis and minicab
legislation, announced yesterday.
Mr Steven Norris, a junior transport minister, called for the views of taxi
users, drivers' organisations and others as part of a review of taxi and
minicab legislation, much of it more than 100 years old.
'The law on taxis and private hire vehicles (minicabs) is a mess,' he said.
'It is antiquated, complicated, difficult to understand and enforce and
totally unsatisfactory.' He called for an end to 'outdated or unnecessary
controls.'
The government is proud of the regulations, which have meant that the most
modern taxis are accessible to people in wheelchairs. But the complete
removal of all restrictions on the type of vehicle that can be used as a
taxi cab is one of several options in a green paper published yesterday.
A casualty of the review could be The Knowledge, the mental map of London's
streets that taxi drivers in the capital often spend three years acquiring.
The government questions whether drivers' knowledge needs to be so
exhaustive.
One of the main issues to be looked at under the review will be whether
taxis and minicabs should continue to be licensed separately. The
distinction between the two has become increasingly blurred.
The different rules governing the two types of vehicle have been a source of
anger, particularly for taxi drivers, who have more onerous regulations.
One option is for the regime in place in London, where taxis and their
drivers are tightly controlled but minicabs are subject to minimum
regulation, to be extended to the rest of the country. Another is for the
system operating in the provinces, where minicabs are more tightly
controlled, to be brought into London.
Mr Norris said the government had not made up its mind which system to adopt
but the green paper declares a preference for a single regime to cover
England and Wales.
The review will also look at the special design of licensed taxis, the need
for identification marks on minicabs, standards of driver fitness and the
need for limits on the number of licences issued.
</TEXT>
<XX>
