<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Home-buyers' costs fall: TSB index says owners need to spend
less than ever on a mortgage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POTENTIAL first-time house buyers need to spend less than ever on a
mortgage, says research which suggests that the affordability of homes is
improving twice as quickly as other measures suggest.
The TSB's quarterly Affordability Index, launched yesterday, shows that
would-be home owners need to spend an average of 26 per cent of their
take-home pay on a mortgage. This is down from 38 per cent a year ago and 67
per cent in the first quarter of 1990, when interest rates were at a peak.
Evidence that first-time buyers have 'never had it so good' is important. Mr
John Wriglesworth, housing analyst at stockbrokers UBS, said: 'It is the key
to recovery and possibly to ending the negative equity nightmare further up
the chain.'
The TSB said that simple house price-to-earnings ratios suggested an
improvement of just one-third since 1989. Yet the new index, compiled by Mr
John Stewart, a housing consultant, showed an improvement of nearly
two-thirds.
The survey gives some examples of how the housing market has changed. In
spring 1989, it says, a single woman in her 20s in the south-east would have
needed 116 per cent of her take-home pay to buy a typical first-time
property. Now she would need 38 per cent. The TSB index's average first-time
buyer earns Pounds 15,100 a year, has monthly take-home pay of Pounds 915
and spends Pounds 242 on a mortgage for an average Pounds 48,800 first-time
buyer property.
The bank said that, in spite of price rises in the past year, affordability
had improved because interest rates had fallen.
Mr Stewart said: 'It's clear that during the false dawn early last year,
when the market looked like it was going to recover, affordability was still
poor . . . but now property prices do not need to fall further on grounds of
affordability.'
The Lord Chancellor's Department yesterday announced a 6.5 per cent fall in
mortgage possession actions in county courts - from 34,535 in the third
quarter of 1992 to 32,276 in July-September this year.
</TEXT>
