<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Union warns over IBM threat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STAFF AT the computer unit of the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency in
Swansea face losing union recognition if IBM, which does not recognise
unions, beats two other bidders to take over the unit.
Many of the 360 staff at the computer unit will take industrial action
tomorrow against privatisation after an 83 per cent vote in favour among
members of the NUCPS civil service union.
The union said that if IBM won it would mean further action. The two other
US companies bidding for the contract, Computer Sciences and EDS-Scicon,
have said they would negotiate with the union if they won.
Meanwhile, employees of IBM could wait 10 years for promotion, Sir Anthony
Cleaver, its UK chairman, warned yesterday.
Sir Anthony, delivering a speech to the Institute of Personnel Management
conference at Harrogate, North Yorkshire, said the company's new four-tier
management structure meant that there were only three levels between
salesmen and the chairman.
The company has undergone a reorganisation of management structures,
removing tiers of management to produce a 'flatter' hier-archy.
The restructuring coincided with IBM reducing its UK workforce from 18,500
in 1989 to 12,000 in a four-year period through voluntary redundancies.
Sir Anthony recognised the difficulties of maintaining motivation for
employees working in a 'delayered' company.
'A four-tier management structure means a maximum of one promotion every 10
years and even that is for the one man who makes it to the top. I wonder
whether we really know how to handle this?'
Changes to IBM's revenue base - only 51 per cent came from hardware last
year - had meant heavy investment in training.
</TEXT>
