FT  28 OCT 93 / Politics accused of 'crippling' the NHS
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POLITICAL interference is crippling the National Health Service, its former
personnel director said yesterday.
Mr Eric Caines, head of the Centre for Health Service Mangement, described
politics, in a study published yesterday, as the 'great inhibitor' in the
running of the NHS.
Mr Caines suggested that political considerations were breeding undue
caution among personnel officers who had become more concerned with
shielding and sheltering managers than with helping them take new
directions.
'When the politics factor is combined with the vast degree of centralisation
which is the general pattern in the public sector, and certainly within the
NHS, the effect at field level is crippling,' he said.
The health service would remain 'low-key and cautious' in its approach to
new developments which might raise the political temperature. 'It is
difficult to see how, all else being equal, it is going to change in the
foreseeable future.'
Mr Caines also attacked centralised pay structures: 'Can any system ever
have been better devised to stifle initiative and imagination and to breed
frustration?'
