<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Danish order gains subsidy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MIKE SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COAL will receive government subsidies for an order to supply coal
to a Danish electricity generator.
The government's decision, announced yesterday by Mr Tim Eggar, energy
minister, will encourage hopes among other potential coal buyers, including
UK industrial companies, that their purchases will also qualify for
subsidies.
It indicates that the government is taking a more lenient view on which
deals it is prepared to subsidise than it indicated when it introduced the
coal subsidy scheme last March.
Ministers originally suggested they were prepared to grant subsidies of up
to Pounds 500m for contracts between British Coal and UK electricity
generators. In the absence of such deals, however, ministers have granted
subsidies to two other types of contract. The first, announced last week,
was for a contract between British Coal and Alcan, an industrial company.
The Danish deal involves British Coal exporting 100,000 tonnes of coal. Some
of the exports will be produced by opencast operations and so will not
qualify for the subsidy.
It is thought the government has provided British Coal with about half of
the difference between the cost of producing the coal and the selling price.
Both the Alcan and Danish deal subsidies are for coal mined from Ellington,
Northumberland.
