<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Great and good control Tory asset vehicle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORDS, KNIGHTS and senior military officials are among those who nominally
control the vehicle which owns the principal assets of the Conservative
party.
Documents obtained from Companies House show that Bourne Association, a
private limited company, is the most important of a number of companies
intimately linked to the Conservative party.
Mr Lewis Fialko, the accountant who audits Bourne, is a shareholder despite
possible breaches of guidelines on independence.
Bourne was formally identified as a 'quasi-subsidiary' when disclosed as
part of an initiative to provide greater financial information in the 1993
Conservative party accounts. The company owns the leasehold on Conservative
Central Office, which was valued in the Bourne accounts for the year to
March 31 1992 at Pounds 7.25m, down from Pounds 12.5m in the previous year.
The Conservative accounts, for the year to March 31 1993, show the property
has again been revalued downwards to Pounds 5.25m.
The Bourne documents also show that the Royal Bank of Scotland, with which
the Conservative party had a Pounds 15.3m overdraft in the 1993 accounts,
has a charge over the office. It shows the building as a leasehold dated in
1958 between London County Council and Limes Property Investments.
There are 26 issued shares in Bourne, held by individuals which in 1991
included Lords Beaverbrook and Chelmer, Major-General Sir Brian
Wyldbore-Smith, former director of the Conservative party's board of
finance, and Major-General H. Ramsay, who gives his address as Conservative
Central Office.
Bourne Association is one of five 'quasi-subsidiaries' from which the party
draws financial benefit, although there is no direct shareholding by the
Conservatives. There are two other so-called river companies: Colne
Association and Arun Association.
Their articles of association are broadly the same as Bourne, showing that
they exist to 'promote the welfare of the British peoples . . . free
enterprise and individual freedom and liberty . . . and further the objects
of the Conservative and Unionist Party'.
They say they accept gifts which they will maintain as long as they think
fit, and give away all or any of their property or assets necessary to
promote their objectives.
Accountancy column, Page 14
</TEXT>
