<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Go-ahead by BP for N Sea platform
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
CONTRACTS for construction of the platform for the North Sea's Andrew Field
were placed yesterday by BP Exploration, the operator.
The company placed the contract for the steel jacket with Highland
Fabricators of Nigg, Ross-shire, and for the deck with Trafalgar House of
Teesside. The 25-month construction phase begins next summer.
Development of the Andrew field, 140 miles north-east of Aberdeen, has yet
to be given board approval, but construction work could also begin next
summer.
The two losers in the order battle are the UIE yard, at Clydebank, Glasgow,
which bid for the deck, and the Italian company Belleli, which bid for the
jacket.
Highland Fabricators, which employs 800, said the order provided work
equivalent to between 350 and 400 jobs.
No figures were disclosed, but the deck order is thought to be worth Pounds
100m and the support structure Pounds 25m.
The value of the UK's North Sea oil reserves fell by 7 per cent last month
because of declining oil prices and a stronger pound, economists at the
Royal Bank of Scotland said yesterday in its monthly North Sea index.
Output from production platforms in the North Sea was valued at Pounds 21.2m
a day, compared with Pounds 22.9m in August. But gas production rose by 23
per cent to a four-month peak as more gas fields came on stream and output
rose to meet winter demand.
The gas was worth Pounds 8m a day, giving a total oil and gas production
value of Pounds 29.1m.
</TEXT>
