<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / World Trade News: Mexico to join 'border bank'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US and Mexico yesterday announced agreement on setting up a North
American Development Bank to help finance environmental and infrastructure
projects along their border.
The Nadbank, along with a new Border Environmental Co-operation Commission,
is expected to play a critical role in winning support for the imperilled
North American Free Trade Agreement between the US, Mexico and Canada.
A Nadbank was originally proposed by Congressman Esteban Torres of
California. Its establishment has won his endorsement of Nafta and other
undecided Hispanic Congressmen may follow suit.
Yesterday's announcement also triggered the endorsements of the National
Council of La Raza, the biggest US Hispanic organisation, and of
environmental groups such as the National Wildlife Federation and the
Natural Resources Defence Council.
Waverers have come down on both sides of the fence, but Nafta opponents
still outnumber its supporters in Congress, particularly in the House of
Representatives.
Mr Jeffrey Shafer, assistant US Treasury secretary for international
affairs, said Mexico and the US would each contribute Dollars 225m (Pounds
149m) over four years in paid-up capital to Nadbank. 'Through market
borrowings, we believe we can leverage the paid-in capital into Dollars 2bn
initially, perhaps eventually up to Dollars 3bn.'
Nadbank loans or guarantees would back around Dollars 2bn of environmental
infrastructure projects along the border.
</TEXT>
