<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / World Trade News: US blocks international fair tax plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EFFORTS to impose multilateral discipline on governments which unfairly tax
foreign companies are in jeopardy following a US decision to opt out of that
part of the Uruguay Round package.
Negotiators said yesterday other countries in the Uruguay Round of talks on
world trade liberalisation might have no choice but to follow the US lead,
leaving multinational companies vulnerable to tax discrimination wherever
they are based.
The issue has become sensitive over the past year, following threats by the
US administration to boost taxes on foreign companies operating in the US.
This is based on allegations that foreign companies engineer comparative
advantage against local rivals by manipulating their accounts between
different national jurisdictions to minimise tax exposure in the US.
The US decision to press for an opt-out for that part of the proposed
Uruguay Round services agreement which guarantees that foreign companies are
in general terms treated in the same way as local companies comes after
months of haggling over clauses which protect national independence on tax
policy. Consensus was reached last week, with the single exception of the
US.
A negotiator said that after opting out, the US treasury would be able to
discriminate as it liked in tax policy without facing the danger of a
challenge through Gatt's dispute settlement system. 'They say they would not
abuse their freedom, but other countries have got reason to be nervous,' he
said.
Critics of the US say such an opt-out would be illegal in other contexts.
For example, no government would be allowed to levy value added tax at a
higher rate on foreign companies than on local companies.
'We knew the US had problems, but didn't expect them to take such a radical
position,' an EC negotiator said.
Gatt officials say the new draft clause does nothing to curb national
autonomy to treat foreign and local companies differently, so long as
differences are not arbitrary or protectionism in disguise. Discrimination
would be legitimate if it were intended to ensure 'equitable or effective'
collection of taxes, to safeguard the tax base, or pre-empt tax evasion.
</TEXT>
