<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / World Trade News: 'Bribery' charge against Mexico
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA BRANSTEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CORRUPTION in Mexico yesterday resurfaced as an issue in the debate over
Nafta as a congressional committee heard from a businessman who claimed he
was offered the chance to pay a bribe while representing IBM.
Congressman John LaFalce, the anti-Nafta chairman of the House committee on
small business, brought Mr Kaveh Moussavi to testify because of concerns
about Mexican corruption and the 'safety of the air-travelling public in and
out of Mexico'.
Mr Moussavi, who acted as an agent for IBM in an attempt to renew Mexico's
air traffic control system, repeated charges that he was asked by men he
said were Mexican officials for a Dollars 1m (Pounds 662,000) payment to the
government's solidarity programme to secure the Dollars 21m contract for the
US computer maker. 'If this is what the government of Mexico is capable of
doing to a Dollars 75bn company. . . what hope is there for your
constituency?' he asked.
An official of the Mexican government called the allegations unfounded and
said they had been reviewed by the Mexican controller general and the
Congress.
Mr Moussavi said he had IBM documents asserting the Mexican air traffic
control system represented a 'menace to the air travelling public' because
the existing computer and radar systems were not integrated.
This charge was disputed by Congressman Joel Hefley, who said he had a
document saying IBM 'had no reason to believe the current air traffic
control system was unsafe'.
