<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Chretien says No to helicopter order
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Jean Chretien, Canada's prime minister-elect, yesterday reaffirmed his
intention to cancel a CDollars 5.8bn (Pounds 2.9bn) order for 50
European-built helicopters shortly after his Liberal party takes office
towards the end of next week.
The Liberals won 178 out of 295 seats in last Monday's general election.
Cancellation of the helicopter order was among the Liberals' most frequently
repeated campaign promises.
The European consortium, led by the UK's Westland Group and Agusta of Italy,
together with its main Canadian partner, Paramax of Montreal, had hoped to
make a last-ditch appeal to Mr Chretien to include the helicopter order in a
wide-ranging defence policy review.
Speaking at a press conference in Ottawa, Mr Chretien said he would discuss
implementation of the North American Free Trade Agreement with President
Bill Clinton in Seattle on November 19.
Although the Liberals plan to seek a a renegotiation of both the 1989
US-Canada free trade agreement and Nafta, which includes Mexico, Mr Chretien
hinted that the new government would avoid any precipitate action.
He noted that under the 1989 deal, the US must negotiate a subsidies and
anti-dumping code within seven years. 'This is a treaty with the US and they
have to proceed with it,' he said.
Business leaders believe the new cabinet will be more sympathetic to
business than the interventionist Trudeau administration, the last Liberal
government. 'Times have changed immensely,' said Mr Tim Reid, Canadian
Chamber of Commerce president. 'I think the Liberals have learned something
from being in opposition for nine years.'
At least two economic ministries are expected to be filled by veteran MPs
with backgrounds in commerce and industry. Mr Paul Martin, who ran one of
Canada's biggest shipping lines before entering politics, is a leading
contender for the finance or industry portfolio.
Mr Roy MacLaren, who is expected to become either trade or industry
minister, is a shareholder in a Toronto publishing business.
