<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Bank fraud victims greet decision with jubilation or dismay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CREDITORS to BCCI were sharply divided yesterday at the outcome of the
Luxembourg ruling, which will delay their receipt of any dividends from the
collapsed bank.
Mr Adil Elias was jubilant at the news. One of the three who brought the
appeal, he is an engineering consultant fromOrlando, Florida, and has been
at the centre of the campaign to fight for a greater contribution from the
government of Abu Dhabi, the majority shareholder.
He was also elected to the BCCI creditors' committee at a meeting of
worldwide creditors in Wembley arena in May this year, when it was disclosed
that the amount the bank owed him was almost Dollars 2m.
The second man, who also stood as candidate for the creditors' committee but
withdrew, was Mr Hal Skolnik, a creditor in his own right and a director of
a company called Sheerbonnet. The third, Mr Assilaos Artiki, is a Greek
insurance broker.
Other creditors were clearly dismayed there would now be further delays
before they received back any of the money they had lost.
Mr Brian Smallridge, finance director of Bury metropolitan district council
and one of the six members of the British creditors' committee recognised by
the courts, said yesterday he was surprised and disappointed at the result.
Bury was one of the 30 UK local authorities which lost money in BCCI.
Referring to hopes that the UK government would seek a better deal with Abu
Dhabi, Mr Smallridge said yesterday: 'We would be delighted if Mr Major
could come back with a large amount of money, but I don't know what
influence he has.'
He expressed surprise that Mr Elias should claim support from most of the
creditors, pointing to a ballot of creditors last year, in which 93 per cent
of those responding approved of the plan.
But Mr Tony Scott, secretary of the BCCI Depositors Association and a member
of the creditors' committee, said he was pleased the Luxembourg court had
taken 'an independent line', because the settlement had been 'grossly
inadequate'. Now was the time for the creditor committees to take the lead,
he added.
Mr Donald Macleod, convener of the Western Isles council, which lost Pounds
24m as a result of the bank's collapse, expressed disappointment at the
court decision. 'The council, in common with the majority of BCCI investors,
agreed to accept the liquidator's proposal, not because it was ideal, but
because it was the best offer available and, indeed, the only realistic
course of action open to it,' he said.
</TEXT>
