<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Australia revises inflation to 3%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMILIA TAGAZA
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MELBOURNE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE AUSTRALIAN government has revised its inflation forecast for 1993-94 to
3 per cent, down from its budget calculation of 3.5 per cent.
The revision followed the announcement from the official statistics bureau
that the consumer price index rose by only 0.6 per cent in the September
quarter, bringing the annual inflation rate to 2.2 per cent during the
quarter.
This is below all expectations of the market, which has been worried about
the weak Australian dollar during the past six months and about a federal
government budget loaded with new tax measures.
The biggest price rises were in tobacco products, meats and vegetables, and
motor vehicles. Price declines were biggest in mortgage interest rates,
credit card charges, clothing and pharmaceutical goods.
Australian business and trade unions have kept up the pressure on the
government of Mr Paul Keating to cut interest rates and kick along the slow
economic recovery.
More encouraging news concerned the official figures on skilled vacancies,
which have risen in two consecutive months. The September figure was 32 per
cent higher than a year ago.
</TEXT>
