<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Polisario pulls out of Western Sahara talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS, UN Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UNITED Nations efforts to resolve the long-standing dispute over the former
Spanish territory of Western Sahara suffered a sharp setback yesterday after
the Polisario Front refused to enter scheduled talks with Morocco.
Initiated three months ago in the Western Sahara capital, Laayoune, these
were to have resumed in New York on Monday in the presence of the UN
mediator, Mr Sahabzada Yaqub-Khan, a former foreign minister of Pakistan.
But the Polisario declined to participate because the Moroccan delegation
included former officials of the nationalist movement who have thrown in
their lot with Morocco, which claims sovereignty over the territory.
Announcing the breakdown, Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, the UN secretary
general, spoke of a 'critical' situation.
But he reaffirmed his determination to work for the UN-supervised referendum
which was supposed to have been held almost two years ago but which
continues to be held up by a dispute over who should be entitled to vote.
Mr Boutros Ghali, who has returned to New York from London following an
extensive trip abroad, including a visit to Somalia, was to report on the
crisis and other issues arising from his visits to a meeting of the Security
Council last night.
</TEXT>
