<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 93 / Travellers warned to avoid Algeria
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS, Middle East Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN and other EC countries yesterday warned their nationals to avoid
Algeria unless absolutely necessary because of the recent wave of killings
and kidnappings.
The warning coincided with a report from Amnesty International which told
the Algerian authorities that 'no level of opposition violence, no matter
how horrifying, can be used to justify torture, summary executions and
unfair trials'.
The EC countries are seeking Algerian help in providing additional security
for their nationals, following the kidnapping on Sunday of three employees
of the French consulate in Algiers. No news of the three, all French
nationals, has been received since they were seized.
'Visitors are advised to postpone all but essential visits to Algeria, where
there have recently been a number of terrorist attacks on foreign
residents,' the Foreign Office in London said yesterday.
France has urged families of its expatriates in Algeria to take advantage of
school holidays to return home.
Algeria has blamed Moslem extremists for the murders of two French
surveyors, two Russian army officers and three oil workers employed by an
Italian company.
In its report Amnesty International said hundreds of people had been
sentenced to death this year in Algeria by courts which violated
requirements of international law.
</TEXT>
